{"title_page": "\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?", "text_new": "{{short description|Resounding inquiry by Juan Carlos I to Hugo Chavez}}\n{{bots|deny=Monkbot6}}<!-- keep Monkbot task 6 from visiting this page -->\n[[File:Cumbre Iberoamericana 2007.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Ibero-American Summit, 2007: Juan Carlos, Zapatero and Ch\u00e1vez are seated on the right side of the chamber. (Ch\u00e1vez is seated at the table in the bottom-right corner clapping.)]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{lang|es|'''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?'''}} ({{IPA-es|po\u027e\u02c8ke no te \u02c8ka\u028eas}}, English: \"Why don't you shut up?\") is a phrase that was uttered by [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|King Juan Carlos I]] of [[Spain]] to [[Venezuela]]n President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], at the 2007 [[Ibero-American Summit]] in [[Santiago, Chile]], when Ch\u00e1vez was repeatedly interrupting Prime Minister of Spain [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]]'s speech. The phrase drew international attention and widespread praise across the world. Following international attention and praise, it became an overnight sensation, gaining [[Cult following|cult status]] as a mobile-phone [[ringtone]]; spawning a [[domain name]]; a contest; T-shirt sales; a television program; and [[YouTube]] videos.\n\n== Incident ==\nAt the meeting on 10 November 2007, Ch\u00e1vez repeatedly interrupted Zapatero to call Zapatero's predecessor, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]], a \"fascist\" and \"less human than snakes\",<ref name=ShutUpBBC>{{cite news\n |url         = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7089131.stm\n |title       = Shut up, Spain king tells Chavez\n |date        = 10 November 2007\n |publisher   = BBC\n |accessdate  = 9 November 2007\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071111194305/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7089131.stm\n |archivedate = 11 November 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> and accuse Aznar of having supported a [[2002 Venezuelan coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|failed coup d'\u00e9tat aimed at removing Ch\u00e1vez from power]].  Zapatero had earlier irritated Ch\u00e1vez by suggesting that Latin America needed to attract more [[foreign portfolio investment|foreign capital]] to combat its \"chronic, deepening poverty\", and claimed that Ch\u00e1vez's policies scared investors out of Latin America.<ref name=ShutUpBBC /><ref name=TimeRebuke>{{cite news|author=Padgett, Tim|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1682967,00.html?imw=Y|title=Behind the King's Rebuke to Ch\u00e1vez|accessdate=14 November 2007|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=12 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115094835/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1682967,00.html?imw=Y|archivedate=15 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCh\u00e1vez's attacks became so strong that Zapatero rose to Aznar's defence, even though he had been severely critical of Aznar in the past. Zapatero pointed out that Aznar had been democratically elected and was \"a legitimate representative of the Spanish people\".<ref name=ShutUpBBC />\n\nAlthough organizers switched off Ch\u00e1vez's microphone, he continued to interrupt as Zapatero defended Aznar. Juan Carlos leaned forward, turned towards his fellow head of state, and said, \"{{lang|es|\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?}}\" The king's rebuke received applause from the general audience.<ref name=TimeRebuke /> He addressed Ch\u00e1vez using the [[T\u2013V distinction|familiar form of \"you\"]].  (In Spanish, {{lang|es|t\u00fa}} and {{lang|es|te}} are usually used in informal chat, among young people or when addressing close friends, family, or children, and can be perceived as insulting when used in other circumstances. However, in Spain the use of \"{{lang|es|t\u00fa}}\" is more extended and considered the standard.)<ref name=ShutUpBBC /> Shortly thereafter, he left the hall, when Nicaraguan President [[Daniel Ortega]] accused Spain of intervention in his country's elections and complained about the presence of Spanish energy companies in Nicaragua.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antena3.com/a3noticias/servlet/Noticias?destino=../a3n/noticia/noticia.jsp&sidicom=si&id=13286798|title=El Rey Don Juan Carlos a Hugo Ch\u00e1vez: \"''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?''\"|accessdate=11 November 2007|publisher=[[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]]|date=11 November 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071112090430/http://www.antena3.com/a3noticias/servlet/Noticias?destino=..%2Fa3n%2Fnoticia%2Fnoticia.jsp&sidicom=si&id=13286798|archivedate=12 November 2007|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> The incident was unprecedented, as never before had the king displayed such anger in public.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elperiodico.com/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=46&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=457570&idseccio_PK=1007 |title=Nunca se hab\u00eda visto al Rey tan enfadado en p\u00fablico |author=Tabar, Carmen |publisher=El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya |date=10 November 2007 |accessdate=10 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208073548/http://www.elperiodico.com/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=46&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=457570&idseccio_PK=1007 |archivedate=8 December 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor the king, the incident was part of an ''[[Annus horribilis#Juan Carlos I of Spain|annus horribilis]]'' for the royal image, according to the Chilean newspaper ''[[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)|La Naci\u00f3n]]''.<ref name=\"La Naci\u00f3n\">{{cite news | url = http://www.lanacion.cl/prontus_noticias_v2/site/artic/20071115/pags/20071115203346.html | title = El 'annus horribilis' del Rey Juan Carlos | publisher = [[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)]] | date = 15 November 2007 | accessdate = 17 February 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20121206025748/http://www.lanacion.cl/prontus_noticias_v2/site/artic/20071115/pags/20071115203346.html | archivedate = 6 December 2012 | df = dmy-all |language=es}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' analyzed the incident, arguing that it exposed \"the unendingly complicated relations between Spain and [[Spanish Empire|its former colonies]]\".<ref name=\"Colonies\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/weekinreview/25romero.html|work=The New York Times|author=Romero, Simon|date=25 November 2007|title=When a Mother Country Tells Its Kid, 'Shut Up'|accessdate=26 February 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215071736/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/weekinreview/25romero.html|archivedate=15 December 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reaction ==\nAfter the events at the summit, Hugo Ch\u00e1vez made statements against King Juan Carlos I, questioning his democratic [[Legitimacy (political science)|legitimacy]], and whether he knew about and endorsed the attempted coup d'\u00e9tat in Venezuela in 2002. Ch\u00e1vez defended his accusations against Aznar, arguing that prohibiting criticism of an elected official such as Aznar would be similar to prohibiting criticism of Hitler. He stated that he would revise Venezuela's position towards Spain and increase surveillance of the activities of Spanish companies in Venezuela, where Spain had been the main investor and trade partner in the last decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Chavez/carga/Rey/avisa/revisara/relaciones/Espana/elpepiesp/20071115elpepinac_2/Tes |work=El Pa\u00eds |title=Ch\u00e1vez carga contra el Rey y avisa de que revisar\u00e1 las relaciones con Espa\u00f1a |date=15 November 2007 |accessdate=15 November 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725171522/http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Chavez/carga/Rey/avisa/revisara/relaciones/Espana/elpepiesp/20071115elpepinac_2/Tes |archivedate=25 July 2008 |df=dmy-all |language=es}}</ref>\n\nThe Spanish government showed appreciation for the reaction of the king and for Zapatero's defense of the dignity of Spanish elected representatives like Aznar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Moratinos/afirma/ultimo/debe/hacerse/llamar/embajador/consultas/elpepuesp/20071115elpepunac_3/Tes|work=El Pa\u00eds|title=Moratinos afirma que \"lo \u00faltimo que debe hacerse\" es llamar al embajador a consultas|date=15 November 2007|accessdate=15 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016143632/http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Moratinos/afirma/ultimo/debe/hacerse/llamar/embajador/consultas/elpepuesp/20071115elpepunac_3/Tes|archivedate=16 October 2008|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days after the event, Ch\u00e1vez demanded an apology from King Juan Carlos and warned Spain that he would review diplomatic ties and take action against Spanish investments such as [[Grupo Santander|Banco Santander]] and [[Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria]] in Venezuela.<ref name=ReconsiderTies /> He accused the king of displaying the kind of\nSpanish arrogance that led to Spain's ejection from South America at the hands of Venezuela's hero, [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]].<ref name=ReconsiderTies>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/15/world/americas/15venez.html?ref=world|title=Ch\u00e1vez Threatens to Reconsider Venezuela's Ties With Spain|agency=Reuters|work=The New York Times|date=15 November 2007|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101110226/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/15/world/americas/15venez.html?ref=world|archivedate=1 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Spanish diplomats were concerned that Ch\u00e1vez may replace his socialism and attacks on \"American Imperialism\" with attacks on what he called \"Spanish imperialism\".<ref name=FTConquer /> Speaking about Venezuela's indigenous peoples, Ch\u00e1vez said of the Spanish, \"They slit our people's throats and chopped them into little bits and left them on the outskirts of towns and villages \u2013 that was what the Spanish empire did here\".<ref name=FTConquer /> The Spanish foreign ministry denied that the \"{{lang|es|\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?}}\" incident was indicative of Spanish\u2013Latin American relations.<ref name=FTConquer /> Some analysts say Ch\u00e1vez used such incidents to \"fire up his support base among the majority poor at home with blunt language that played on their misgivings of rich countries' investments in Latin America\".<ref name=ReconsiderTies />\n\nAccording to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', it is uncertain which of the two men came out of the incident looking worse: \"Ch\u00e1vez for his boorish lack of etiquette\",<ref name=BattleRoyal /> or the king for insulting another leader. The king's words raised questions as the \"200th anniversary of independence for the former Spanish colonies\" approached.<ref name=BattleRoyal /> Several days after the incident, Venezuela's state-run television ran footage of Juan Carlos with [[Francisco Franco]]. The king was depicted as the dictator's lackey; but the fact that the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]], which preserved the monarchy, had been approved by a referendum; and the key role played by the king in putting down an [[23-F|attempted military coup in 1981]], were not mentioned.<ref name=BattleRoyal />\n\nThe king's outburst received divided reactions from other leaders. Brazil's President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] defended Ch\u00e1vez, while Peru's and El Salvador's presidents [[Alan Garc\u00eda]] and [[Antonio Saca]] supported the king.<ref name=BattleRoyal />\n\nAn editor for the ''[[Washington Post]]'' noted the \"Spanish-speaking world has been abuzz about [this] verbal slapdown\" and suggested that King Juan Carlos \"should have asked the assembled heads of state: 'Why don't you speak up?'\"<ref>Jackson Diehl, \"Silencing Venezuela's President a Royal Task\", 21 November 2007, syndicated in the ''[[Albuquerque Journal]]'', p. A9.</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n=== Immediate ===\nOne week after the event, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote that King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia]] delivered Ch\u00e1vez's second rebuke from a king in one week, when he reminded Ch\u00e1vez that oil should not be used as a tool for conflict. The remarks came minutes after Ch\u00e1vez called for [[OPEC]] to \"assert itself as an active political agent\" at the OPEC summit in Saudi Arabia's capital, Riyadh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119532579754096997?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Chavez's OPEC Speech Spurs Rebuke From Saudi King|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=17 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507100343/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119532579754096997?mod=googlenews_wsj|archivedate=7 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a followup at the OPEC summit, ''[[Reuters]]'' wrote that \"Spain's king cannot shut Chavez up but bladder can\",<ref name=Bladder>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUKN1947231020071119|title=Spain's king cannot shut Chavez up but bladder can|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121110634/http://uk.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUKN1947231020071119|archivedate=21 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and that Ch\u00e1vez said to a throng of reporters at the OPEC summit, \"For a while now, I have needed to go to the bathroom and I am going to pee ... Do you want me to pee on you?\"<ref name=Bladder />\n\nTwo weeks after the event, Chile's President [[Michelle Bachelet]] revealed that she had politely requested that Ch\u00e1vez abstain from making some statements at the summit, indicating frankly that she felt \"let down\" by the subsequent discussions at the OPEC meeting, considering the effect that the price of oil has on countries like Chile.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercopress.com/vernoticia.do?id=11957&formato=HTML|title=Bachelet also asked Chavez, (politely) to shut up|publisher=MercoPress|date=23 November 2007|accessdate=23 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127141358/http://www.mercopress.com/vernoticia.do?id=11957&formato=html|archivedate=27 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also just weeks after the incident, Ch\u00e1vez was \"accused of breaking a protocol accord\" with Colombia's [[\u00c1lvaro Uribe V\u00e9lez|President \u00c1lvaro Uribe]] and \"exhaust[ing] his Colombian counterpart's patience by speaking out of turn once too often\", formally ending Ch\u00e1vez's mediation in hostage negotiations with the Colombian [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) guerrilla group.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hudson, Saul|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/politicsNews/idUSN2224925520071122?sp=true|title=Colombian mediation failure hurts talkative Chavez|agency=Reuters|date=22 November 2007|accessdate=23 November 2007}}</ref> (Dialogue resumed later and the hostages were freed in January 2008.)\n\n=== Enduring ===\nIn 2013, Infobae named the incident among those most noted to have captured public attention in the history of the Ibero-American Summit.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.infobae.com/2013/10/18/1517127-cumbre-papelones-del-por-que-no-te-callas-al-intercambio-corbatas-aznar-y-fidel |title= Cumbre de papelones: del \"\u00bfpor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" al intercambio de corbatas entre Aznar y Fidel |date= 18 October 2013 |accessdate= 14 November 2013 |publisher= infobae |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131024222814/http://www.infobae.com/2013/10/18/1517127-cumbre-papelones-del-por-que-no-te-callas-al-intercambio-corbatas-aznar-y-fidel |archivedate= 24 October 2013 |df= dmy-all |language=es}}</ref>  ''Entorno Inteligente'' invoked the phrase, paying homage to Spain for the \"immortal lexicon\", and referring to Venezuelan politician [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] as {{lang|es|inmaduro}} (immature).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.entornointeligente.com/articulo/1572136/Por-que-no-te-callas-inMaduro-02112013 |date= 2 November 2013 |accessdate= 14 November 2013 |title= \u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas, in\u2212Maduro? |publisher= Entorno Inteligente |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140714201518/http://www.entornointeligente.com/articulo/1572136/Por-que-no-te-callas-inMaduro-02112013 |archivedate= 14 July 2014 |df= dmy-all |language=es}}</ref> Analitica.com said that language used at the 2013 Summit should be clear, and that the rebuke of Ch\u00e1vez is still remembered.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.analitica.com/va/internacionales/opinion/1054388.asp |publisher=Analitica.com |title= Cumbres Iberoamericanas: Pasado y Futuro  |author= [[Milos Alcalay]] |date= 29 October 2013 |accessdate= 14 November 2013|language=es}}</ref>\n\n== Popularity of phrase ==\nZapatero said he did not realize what an influential moment it had been until he returned home and his eldest daughter greeted him with \"{{lang|es|\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?}}\", which made them both laugh.<ref>{{in lang|es}} Hermoso, Borja. {{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Aznar/Zapatero/eres/presidente/llamas/quieras/elpepuesp/20071113elpepunac_23/Tes|title=Aznar a Zapatero: \"T\u00fa eres el presidente, me llamas cuando quieras\".|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520050307/http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Aznar/Zapatero/eres/presidente/llamas/quieras/elpepuesp/20071113elpepunac_23/Tes|archivedate=20 May 2011|df=dmy-all}} ''El Pa\u00eds'', 13 November 2007. . Retrieved 15 November 2007.</ref>\n\nThe king's phrase gained cult slogan status, ringing from mobile phones; appearing on [[T-shirt]]s; and being used as a greeting. The domain, porquenotecallas.com, had reached US$4,600 on eBay as of 16 November 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cellular-news.com/story/27491.php|title=Regal 'Shut Up' Becomes a Cult Ringtone|date=16 November 2007|publisher=cellular-news.com|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117034044/http://www.cellular-news.com/story/27491.php|archivedate=17 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Corral /> The phrase became a YouTube sensation overnight and a song was written to a traditional tune.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/15/AR2007111501455.html|title='Why Don't You Shut Up?' Chavez's antagonistic antics have their limit|author=Sanchez, Marcela|work=The Washington Post|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820074539/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/15/AR2007111501455.html|archivedate=20 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The phrase has spawned countless media articles, jokes, songs and video clips; while in Spain an estimated 500,000 people downloaded the phrase as a ringtone, generating \u20ac1.5&nbsp;million (US$2&nbsp;million) in sales.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/7101386.stm 'Shut up' Chavez is ringtone hit.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121110534/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/7101386.stm |date=21 November 2007 }} BBC News, 19 November 2007. . Retrieved 19 November 2007.</ref><ref name=Nadie>{{in lang|es}} [http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/spanish/latin_america/newsid_7095000/7095670.stm Ahora nadie se calla.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116085842/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/spanish/latin_america/newsid_7095000/7095670.stm |date=16 November 2007 }} BBC Mundo, 14 November 2007. . Retrieved 15 November 2007.</ref> As of 14 November 2007, Google generated 665,000 webhits on the phrase and YouTube had 610 videos.<ref name=Nadie /> Entrepreneurs in Florida and Texas put the slogan on T-shirts, and marketed them on [[eBay]] and elsewhere;<ref name=\"Colonies\" /> the phrase became a greeting among Venezuelan expats in Miami and Spain<ref name=Corral>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2004017429_ringtone16.html|title=Spanish king's retort to Ch\u00e1vez strikes chord|author=Corral, Oscar|date=13 November 2007|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122152938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2004017429_ringtone16.html|archivedate=22 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and a slogan for Ch\u00e1vez opponents.<ref name=FTConquer>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21822492/|title=Juan Carlos' words conquer the net|work= Financial Times |author=Crawford, Leslie Crawford |date=15 November 2007|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=16 November 2007 |url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071117205413/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21822492/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 17 November 2007}}</ref><ref name=Kingrow>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/7096950.stm Viewpoints: Chavez and King row.] BBC News, 16 November 2007. . Retrieved 17 November 2007.</ref>\n\nLess than 24 hours after the event, the king's words were used by sports commentators during the radio transmission of Spanish language football games to describe controversial events. A contest for the best audiovisual depiction of the event was announced in Spain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://buscador.eluniversal.com/2007/11/13/cyt_ava_tono-de-la-frase-p_13A1191237.shtml|title=Tono de la frase \"\u00bfpor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" arrasa en politon\u00edas de celulares|work=[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]]|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924001929/http://buscador.eluniversal.com/2007/11/13/cyt_ava_tono-de-la-frase-p_13A1191237.shtml |archivedate=24 September 2009|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> ''[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]'' editorial page suggested that the phrase would have the power to change the course of history, as has been credited to [[Ronald Reagan]]'s, \"Mr. Gorbachev, [[tear down this wall!]]\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Royal message to petty dictator: Just shut up|last=Cooklis|first=Ray|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|location=Cincinnati, Ohio|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|page=8B|date=23 November 2007|accessdate=23 November 2007|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CEQB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11D5A7BEB47FB668&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|url-access=subscription |quote=History provides us with many examples of famous catch-phrases \u2013 the right words, uttered at just the right time \u2013 that have shown the power to change the course of events: ... Reagan's 'Mr. Gorbachev, tear down this wall.' Someday soon, we may be able to add to this list the blunt suggestion, already a hot Internet buzz-phrase and cell-phone ring tone, by an exasperated King Juan Carlos I to Venezuelan President Hugo Ch\u00e1vez during a recent summit in Chile: \"Why don't you shut up?\"|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026154535/http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004|archivedate=26 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}<!-- http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071123/EDIT01/711230358/1090/EDIT --></ref>\n\nThe ''Los Angeles Times'' said \"the Spanish-speaking world can hardly stop talking about [the incident]\", which provided \"fodder for satirists from Mexico City to Madrid\".<ref name=BattleRoyal /> The reaction was apparent \"in newspaper headlines, cable television and on YouTube. His phrase was reproduced on T-shirts, and cellphone ring tones. In Mexico City, the dust-up became a satirical skit, \"El Chabo del 8\".<!-- It's SATIRE, PARODY, not the real show! Please leave the typo! --> In El Salvador's capital, the phrase became a playful greeting\".<ref name=BattleRoyal>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-chavez17nov17,1,7510496.story?coll=la-headlines-world|title=King's words to Chavez start a battle royal|work=Los Angeles Times|author=Kraul, Chris|date=17 November 2007|accessdate=17 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206160526/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-chavez17nov17,1,7510496.story?coll=la-headlines-world|archivedate=6 February 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In Australia ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' reported the king could earn a multimillion-euro business if he claimed rights over the phrase, which generated a ''[[Benny Hill Show]]''-style skit and a Nike ad, \"Juan do it. Just shut up\", with the Brazilian football star, [[Ronaldinho]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/why-dont-you-shut-up/2007/11/19/1195321697277.html|title=Royal outburst now a nasty little earner|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=20 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120215037/http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/why-dont-you-shut-up/2007/11/19/1195321697277.html|archivedate=20 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Canada's ''[[CBC News]]'' said an actor's voice was used to mimic the king's voice in the ringtone to avoid legal problems over the use of the phrase, which also generated sales of coffee mugs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/king-of-spain-tells-half-a-million-callers-to-shut-up-1.656819|title='King of Spain' tells half a million callers to 'shut up': New, insulting ringtone a smash hit in Spain|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122183800/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/king-of-spain-tells-half-a-million-callers-to-shut-up-1.656819|archivedate=22 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The infamous phrase was also referred to in a comic song called \"[[Baila el Chiki-chiki]]\", Spain's contribution to [[Eurovision 2008]], and in the song \"La Plata\", by the Brazilian band [[Jota Quest]].\n\nProtesters against the Ch\u00e1vez government adopted the phrase as their slogan;<ref name=Kingrow /> T-shirts in Venezuela had the slogan with the \"{{lang|es|no}}\" in capital letters, representing a call to vote against amendments in the [[2007 Venezuelan constitutional referendum|December 2007 constitutional referendum]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsvine.com/_news/2007/11/19/1108819-shut-up-is-hit-ringtone-in-spain|title=NBC News - Breaking News & Top Stories - Latest World, US & Local News|website=newsvine.com|accessdate=7 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026045539/http://www.newsvine.com/_news/2007/11/19/1108819-shut-up-is-hit-ringtone-in-spain|archivedate=26 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the phrase was used as a taunt when more than 100,000 marched in protest against Ch\u00e1vez's proposed constitutional changes.<ref name=\"MarchTaunt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article2976631.ece|work=The Times|date=30 November 2007|title=100,000 march against Hugo Chavez reforms|accessdate=30 November 2007|location=London|first1=Hannah|last1=Strange|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706165434/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article2976631.ece|archivedate=6 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Argentina, a television program called ''Por qu\u00e9 no te callas'' began broadcasting on 6 December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laflecha.net/canales/comunicacion/noticias/el-por-que-no-te-callas-del-rey-juan-carlos-i-en-la-tv-argentina/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207183842/http://www.laflecha.net/canales/comunicacion/noticias/el-por-que-no-te-callas-del-rey-juan-carlos-i-en-la-tv-argentina|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 December 2007|title=El \"\u00bfpor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" del rey Juan Carlos I, en la TV argentina|work=La Flecha|date=5 December 2007|accessdate=12 January 2008|language=es}}</ref> The phrase was also seen at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://caracas.eluniversal.com/sudafrica10/2010/06/21/sur10_ava_frase-por-que-no-t_21A4063571.shtml |title=Frase \"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" aparece en el Espa\u00f1a \u2013 Honduras |date=21 June 2010 |work=[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624101012/http://caracas.eluniversal.com/sudafrica10/2010/06/21/sur10_ava_frase-por-que-no-t_21A4063571.shtml |archivedate=24 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Colombia, a famous YouTube animation called \"Vulgarcito\" depicted a summit between some Latin American countries and since Hugo Ch\u00e1vez never stopped talking in the animation, Vulgarcito, the main character, slapped him and shouted \"Shhh. It is time to quote the wise King of Spain and ask you: {{lang|es|\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?}}\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JY06ySAnoKw|title=VULGARCITO vs CHAVEZ (original en HQ)|last=cardoto|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=7 May 2018|via=YouTube|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531231747/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JY06ySAnoKw|archivedate=31 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Alternative forms ==\nAccording to ''[[Foundation of Urgent Spanish|Fund\u00e9u BBVA]]'', the Urgent Spanish Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00a1Por qu\u00e9 no te callas!|url=http://www.fundeu.es/Consultas.aspx?frmOpcion=CONSULTA&frmFontSize=2&frmIdConsulta=690|work=Fund\u00e9u|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216015604/http://www.fundeu.es/Consultas.aspx?frmOpcion=CONSULTA&frmFontSize=2&frmIdConsulta=690|archivedate=16 December 2009|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> and the Director of the [[Academia Chilena de la Lengua|Chilean Academy of the Spanish language]],<ref>{{cite web|title=En chileno la frase del rey Juan Carlos ser\u00eda: \u00a1por qu\u00e9 no te call\u00e1i vo!|url=http://www.lun.com/modulos/catalogo/paginas/2007/11/19/LUCPRDI02LU1911.htm?tipoPantalla=1024|work=[[Las \u00daltimas Noticias]]|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071121104137/http://www.lun.com/modulos/catalogo/paginas/2007/11/19/LUCPRDI02LU1911.htm?tipoPantalla=1024 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 21 November 2007|language=es}}</ref> the phrase uttered by the king, given the situation under which it was said, should be written with exclamation marks instead of question marks: {{lang|es|\u00a1Por qu\u00e9 no te callas!}} Alternatively, it could be written using a combination of both exclamation and question marks: {{lang|es|\u00a1\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?!}} or {{lang|es|\u00bf\u00a1Por qu\u00e9 no te callas!?}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spain|Venezuela}}\n*[[Shut up]]\n*[[Spain\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{in lang|es}} [http://www.elpais.com/videos/ultimo/Rey/Chavez/callas/elpvid/20071110elpepuult_8/Ves/ El Rey a Ch\u00e1vez: \"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\"] ''El Pa\u00eds'', 10 November 2007 (no subtitles)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X3Kzbo7tNLg Youtube video of the incident] (English subtitles)\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/18/AR2007111800945.html?hpid=opinionsbox1|title=Ch\u00e1vez and the King|author=Diehl, Jackson|work=The Washington Post|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=10 November 2007|page=A17}}\n\n{{Hugo Ch\u00e1vez}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Por Que No Te Callas}}\n[[Category:2007 in Chile]]\n[[Category:2007 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2007 in politics]]\n[[Category:2007 in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic conferences in Chile]]\n[[Category:Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]]\n[[Category:International disputes]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone culture]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Political Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Spanish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Spain\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n[[Category:Juan Carlos I of Spain]]\n[[Category:2007 in Spain]]\n[[Category:Political quotes]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 2007]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Resounding inquiry by Juan Carlos I to Hugo Chavez}}\n{{bots|deny=Monkbot6}}<!-- keep Monkbot task 6 from visiting this page -->\n[[File:Cumbre Iberoamericana 2007.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Ibero-American Summit, 2007: Juan Carlos, Zapatero and Ch\u00e1vez are seated on the right side of the chamber. (Ch\u00e1vez is seated at the table in the bottom-right corner clapping.)]]\n{{italic title}}\n'''''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?''''' ({{IPA-es|po\u027e\u02c8ke no te \u02c8ka\u028eas}}, English: \"Why don't you shut up?\") is a phrase that was uttered by [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|King Juan Carlos I]] of [[Spain]] to [[Venezuela]]n President [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], at the 2007 [[Ibero-American Summit]] in [[Santiago, Chile]], when Ch\u00e1vez was repeatedly interrupting Prime Minister of Spain [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]]'s speech. The phrase drew international attention and widespread praise across the world. Following international attention and praise, it became an overnight sensation, gaining [[Cult following|cult status]] as a mobile-phone [[ringtone]]; spawning a [[domain name]]; a contest; T-shirt sales; a television program; and [[YouTube]] videos.\n\n== Incident ==\nAt the meeting on 10 November 2007, Ch\u00e1vez repeatedly interrupted Zapatero to call Zapatero's predecessor, [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]], a \"fascist\" and \"less human than snakes\",<ref name=ShutUpBBC>{{cite news\n |url         = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7089131.stm\n |title       = Shut up, Spain king tells Chavez\n |date        = 10 November 2007\n |publisher   = BBC\n |accessdate  = 9 November 2007\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071111194305/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7089131.stm\n |archivedate = 11 November 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> and accuse Aznar of having supported a [[2002 Venezuelan coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|failed coup d'\u00e9tat aimed at removing Ch\u00e1vez from power]].  Zapatero had earlier irritated Ch\u00e1vez by suggesting that Latin America needed to attract more [[foreign portfolio investment|foreign capital]] to combat its \"chronic, deepening poverty\", and claimed that Ch\u00e1vez's policies scared investors out of Latin America.<ref name=ShutUpBBC /><ref name=TimeRebuke>{{cite news|author=Padgett, Tim|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1682967,00.html?imw=Y|title=Behind the King's Rebuke to Ch\u00e1vez|accessdate=14 November 2007|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=12 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115094835/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1682967,00.html?imw=Y|archivedate=15 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCh\u00e1vez's attacks became so strong that Zapatero rose to Aznar's defence, even though he had been severely critical of Aznar in the past. Zapatero pointed out that Aznar had been democratically elected and was \"a legitimate representative of the Spanish people\".<ref name=ShutUpBBC />\n\nAlthough organizers switched off Ch\u00e1vez's microphone, he continued to interrupt as Zapatero defended Aznar. Juan Carlos leaned forward, turned towards his fellow head of state, and said, \"''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?''\" The king's rebuke received applause from the general audience.<ref name=TimeRebuke /> He addressed Ch\u00e1vez using the [[T\u2013V distinction|familiar form of \"you\"]].  (In Spanish, ''t\u00fa'' and ''te'' are usually used in informal chat, among young people or when addressing close friends, family, or children, and can be perceived as insulting when used in other circumstances. However, in Spain the use of \"t\u00fa\" is more extended and considered the standard.)<ref name=ShutUpBBC /> Shortly thereafter, he left the hall, when Nicaraguan President [[Daniel Ortega]] accused Spain of intervention in his country's elections and complained about the presence of Spanish energy companies in Nicaragua.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antena3.com/a3noticias/servlet/Noticias?destino=../a3n/noticia/noticia.jsp&sidicom=si&id=13286798|title=El Rey Don Juan Carlos a Hugo Ch\u00e1vez: \"''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?''\"|accessdate=11 November 2007|publisher=[[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]]|date=11 November 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071112090430/http://www.antena3.com/a3noticias/servlet/Noticias?destino=..%2Fa3n%2Fnoticia%2Fnoticia.jsp&sidicom=si&id=13286798|archivedate=12 November 2007|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> The incident was unprecedented, as never before had the king displayed such anger in public.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elperiodico.com/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=46&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=457570&idseccio_PK=1007 |title=Nunca se hab\u00eda visto al Rey tan enfadado en p\u00fablico |author=Tabar, Carmen |publisher=El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya |date=10 November 2007 |accessdate=10 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208073548/http://www.elperiodico.com/default.asp?idpublicacio_PK=46&idioma=CAS&idnoticia_PK=457570&idseccio_PK=1007 |archivedate=8 December 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor the king, the incident was part of an ''[[Annus horribilis#Juan Carlos I of Spain|annus horribilis]]'' for the royal image, according to the Chilean newspaper ''[[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)|La Naci\u00f3n]]''.<ref name=\"La Naci\u00f3n\">{{cite news | url = http://www.lanacion.cl/prontus_noticias_v2/site/artic/20071115/pags/20071115203346.html | title = El 'annus horribilis' del Rey Juan Carlos | publisher = [[La Naci\u00f3n (Chile)]] | date = 15 November 2007 | accessdate = 17 February 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://archive.today/20121206025748/http://www.lanacion.cl/prontus_noticias_v2/site/artic/20071115/pags/20071115203346.html | archivedate = 6 December 2012 | df = dmy-all |language=es}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' analyzed the incident, arguing that it exposed \"the unendingly complicated relations between Spain and [[Spanish Empire|its former colonies]]\".<ref name=\"Colonies\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/weekinreview/25romero.html|work=The New York Times|author=Romero, Simon|date=25 November 2007|title=When a Mother Country Tells Its Kid, 'Shut Up'|accessdate=26 February 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215071736/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/25/weekinreview/25romero.html|archivedate=15 December 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reaction ==\nAfter the events at the summit, Hugo Ch\u00e1vez made statements against King Juan Carlos I, questioning his democratic [[Legitimacy (political science)|legitimacy]], and whether he knew about and endorsed the attempted coup d'\u00e9tat in Venezuela in 2002. Ch\u00e1vez defended his accusations against Aznar, arguing that prohibiting criticism of an elected official such as Aznar would be similar to prohibiting criticism of Hitler. He stated that he would revise Venezuela's position towards Spain and increase surveillance of the activities of Spanish companies in Venezuela, where Spain had been the main investor and trade partner in the last decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Chavez/carga/Rey/avisa/revisara/relaciones/Espana/elpepiesp/20071115elpepinac_2/Tes |work=El Pa\u00eds |title=Ch\u00e1vez carga contra el Rey y avisa de que revisar\u00e1 las relaciones con Espa\u00f1a |date=15 November 2007 |accessdate=15 November 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725171522/http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Chavez/carga/Rey/avisa/revisara/relaciones/Espana/elpepiesp/20071115elpepinac_2/Tes |archivedate=25 July 2008 |df=dmy-all |language=es}}</ref>\n\nThe Spanish government showed appreciation for the reaction of the king and for Zapatero's defense of the dignity of Spanish elected representatives like Aznar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Moratinos/afirma/ultimo/debe/hacerse/llamar/embajador/consultas/elpepuesp/20071115elpepunac_3/Tes|work=El Pa\u00eds|title=Moratinos afirma que \"lo \u00faltimo que debe hacerse\" es llamar al embajador a consultas|date=15 November 2007|accessdate=15 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016143632/http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Moratinos/afirma/ultimo/debe/hacerse/llamar/embajador/consultas/elpepuesp/20071115elpepunac_3/Tes|archivedate=16 October 2008|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref>\n\nSeveral days after the event, Ch\u00e1vez demanded an apology from King Juan Carlos and warned Spain that he would review diplomatic ties and take action against Spanish investments such as [[Grupo Santander|Banco Santander]] and [[Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria]] in Venezuela.<ref name=ReconsiderTies /> He accused the king of displaying the kind of\nSpanish arrogance that led to Spain's ejection from South America at the hands of Venezuela's hero, [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]].<ref name=ReconsiderTies>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/15/world/americas/15venez.html?ref=world|title=Ch\u00e1vez Threatens to Reconsider Venezuela's Ties With Spain|agency=Reuters|work=The New York Times|date=15 November 2007|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101110226/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/15/world/americas/15venez.html?ref=world|archivedate=1 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Spanish diplomats were concerned that Ch\u00e1vez may replace his socialism and attacks on \"American Imperialism\" with attacks on what he called \"Spanish imperialism\".<ref name=FTConquer /> Speaking about Venezuela's indigenous peoples, Ch\u00e1vez said of the Spanish, \"They slit our people's throats and chopped them into little bits and left them on the outskirts of towns and villages \u2013 that was what the Spanish empire did here\".<ref name=FTConquer /> The Spanish foreign ministry denied that the ''\"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\"'' incident was indicative of Spanish\u2013Latin American relations.<ref name=FTConquer /> Some analysts say Ch\u00e1vez used such incidents to \"fire up his support base among the majority poor at home with blunt language that played on their misgivings of rich countries' investments in Latin America\".<ref name=ReconsiderTies />\n\nAccording to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', it is uncertain which of the two men came out of the incident looking worse: \"Ch\u00e1vez for his boorish lack of etiquette\",<ref name=BattleRoyal /> or the king for insulting another leader. The king's words raised questions as the \"200th anniversary of independence for the former Spanish colonies\" approached.<ref name=BattleRoyal /> Several days after the incident, Venezuela's state-run television ran footage of Juan Carlos with [[Francisco Franco]]. The king was depicted as the dictator's lackey; but the fact that the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978]], which preserved the monarchy, had been approved by a referendum; and the key role played by the king in putting down an [[23-F|attempted military coup in 1981]], were not mentioned.<ref name=BattleRoyal />\n\nThe king's outburst received divided reactions from other leaders. Brazil's President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] defended Ch\u00e1vez, while Peru's and El Salvador's presidents [[Alan Garc\u00eda]] and [[Antonio Saca]] supported the king.<ref name=BattleRoyal />\n\nAn editor for the ''[[Washington Post]]'' noted the \"Spanish-speaking world has been abuzz about [this] verbal slapdown\" and suggested that King Juan Carlos \"should have asked the assembled heads of state: 'Why don't you speak up?'\"<ref>Jackson Diehl, \"Silencing Venezuela's President a Royal Task\", 21 November 2007, syndicated in the ''[[Albuquerque Journal]]'', p. A9.</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n\n=== Immediate ===\nOne week after the event, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote that King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia]] delivered Ch\u00e1vez's second rebuke from a king in one week, when he reminded Ch\u00e1vez that oil should not be used as a tool for conflict. The remarks came minutes after Ch\u00e1vez called for [[OPEC]] to \"assert itself as an active political agent\" at the OPEC summit in Saudi Arabia's capital, Riyadh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119532579754096997?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Chavez's OPEC Speech Spurs Rebuke From Saudi King|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=17 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507100343/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB119532579754096997?mod=googlenews_wsj|archivedate=7 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a followup at the OPEC summit, ''[[Reuters]]'' wrote that \"Spain's king cannot shut Chavez up but bladder can\",<ref name=Bladder>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUKN1947231020071119|title=Spain's king cannot shut Chavez up but bladder can|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121110634/http://uk.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUKN1947231020071119|archivedate=21 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and that Ch\u00e1vez said to a throng of reporters at the OPEC summit, \"For a while now, I have needed to go to the bathroom and I am going to pee ... Do you want me to pee on you?\"<ref name=Bladder />\n\nTwo weeks after the event, Chile's President [[Michelle Bachelet]] revealed that she had politely requested that Ch\u00e1vez abstain from making some statements at the summit, indicating frankly that she felt \"let down\" by the subsequent discussions at the OPEC meeting, considering the effect that the price of oil has on countries like Chile.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercopress.com/vernoticia.do?id=11957&formato=HTML|title=Bachelet also asked Chavez, (politely) to shut up|publisher=MercoPress|date=23 November 2007|accessdate=23 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127141358/http://www.mercopress.com/vernoticia.do?id=11957&formato=html|archivedate=27 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also just weeks after the incident, Ch\u00e1vez was \"accused of breaking a protocol accord\" with Colombia's [[\u00c1lvaro Uribe V\u00e9lez|President \u00c1lvaro Uribe]] and \"exhaust[ing] his Colombian counterpart's patience by speaking out of turn once too often\", formally ending Ch\u00e1vez's mediation in hostage negotiations with the Colombian [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia]] (FARC) guerrilla group.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hudson, Saul|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/politicsNews/idUSN2224925520071122?sp=true|title=Colombian mediation failure hurts talkative Chavez|agency=Reuters|date=22 November 2007|accessdate=23 November 2007}}</ref> (Dialogue resumed later and the hostages were freed in January 2008.)\n\n=== Enduring ===\nIn 2013, Infobae named the incident among those most noted to have captured public attention in the history of the Ibero-American Summit.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.infobae.com/2013/10/18/1517127-cumbre-papelones-del-por-que-no-te-callas-al-intercambio-corbatas-aznar-y-fidel |title= Cumbre de papelones: del \"\u00bfpor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" al intercambio de corbatas entre Aznar y Fidel |date= 18 October 2013 |accessdate= 14 November 2013 |publisher= infobae |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131024222814/http://www.infobae.com/2013/10/18/1517127-cumbre-papelones-del-por-que-no-te-callas-al-intercambio-corbatas-aznar-y-fidel |archivedate= 24 October 2013 |df= dmy-all |language=es}}</ref>  ''Entorno Inteligente'' invoked the phrase, paying homage to Spain for the \"immortal lexicon\", and referring to Venezuelan politician [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] as ''inmaduro'' (immature).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.entornointeligente.com/articulo/1572136/Por-que-no-te-callas-inMaduro-02112013 |date= 2 November 2013 |accessdate= 14 November 2013 |title= \u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas, in\u2212Maduro? |publisher= Entorno Inteligente |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140714201518/http://www.entornointeligente.com/articulo/1572136/Por-que-no-te-callas-inMaduro-02112013 |archivedate= 14 July 2014 |df= dmy-all |language=es}}</ref> Analitica.com said that language used at the 2013 Summit should be clear, and that the rebuke of Ch\u00e1vez is still remembered.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.analitica.com/va/internacionales/opinion/1054388.asp |publisher=Analitica.com |title= Cumbres Iberoamericanas: Pasado y Futuro  |author= [[Milos Alcalay]] |date= 29 October 2013 |accessdate= 14 November 2013|language=es}}</ref>\n\n== Popularity of phrase ==\nZapatero said he did not realize what an influential moment it had been until he returned home and his eldest daughter greeted him with ''\"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\"'', which made them both laugh.<ref>{{in lang|es}} Hermoso, Borja. {{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Aznar/Zapatero/eres/presidente/llamas/quieras/elpepuesp/20071113elpepunac_23/Tes|title=Aznar a Zapatero: \"T\u00fa eres el presidente, me llamas cuando quieras\".|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520050307/http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/Aznar/Zapatero/eres/presidente/llamas/quieras/elpepuesp/20071113elpepunac_23/Tes|archivedate=20 May 2011|df=dmy-all}} ''El Pa\u00eds'', 13 November 2007. . Retrieved 15 November 2007.</ref>\n\nThe king's phrase gained cult slogan status, ringing from mobile phones; appearing on [[T-shirt]]s; and being used as a greeting. The domain, porquenotecallas.com, had reached US$4,600 on eBay as of 16 November 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cellular-news.com/story/27491.php|title=Regal 'Shut Up' Becomes a Cult Ringtone|date=16 November 2007|publisher=cellular-news.com|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117034044/http://www.cellular-news.com/story/27491.php|archivedate=17 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Corral /> The phrase became a YouTube sensation overnight and a song was written to a traditional tune.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/15/AR2007111501455.html|title='Why Don't You Shut Up?' Chavez's antagonistic antics have their limit|author=Sanchez, Marcela|work=The Washington Post|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820074539/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/15/AR2007111501455.html|archivedate=20 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The phrase has spawned countless media articles, jokes, songs and video clips; while in Spain an estimated 500,000 people downloaded the phrase as a ringtone, generating \u20ac1.5&nbsp;million (US$2&nbsp;million) in sales.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/7101386.stm 'Shut up' Chavez is ringtone hit.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121110534/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/7101386.stm |date=21 November 2007 }} BBC News, 19 November 2007. . Retrieved 19 November 2007.</ref><ref name=Nadie>{{in lang|es}} [http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/spanish/latin_america/newsid_7095000/7095670.stm Ahora nadie se calla.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116085842/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/spanish/latin_america/newsid_7095000/7095670.stm |date=16 November 2007 }} BBC Mundo, 14 November 2007. . Retrieved 15 November 2007.</ref> As of 14 November 2007, Google generated 665,000 webhits on the phrase and YouTube had 610 videos.<ref name=Nadie /> Entrepreneurs in Florida and Texas put the slogan on T-shirts, and marketed them on [[eBay]] and elsewhere;<ref name=\"Colonies\" /> the phrase became a greeting among Venezuelan expats in Miami and Spain<ref name=Corral>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2004017429_ringtone16.html|title=Spanish king's retort to Ch\u00e1vez strikes chord|author=Corral, Oscar|date=13 November 2007|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122152938/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2004017429_ringtone16.html|archivedate=22 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and a slogan for Ch\u00e1vez opponents.<ref name=FTConquer>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21822492/|title=Juan Carlos' words conquer the net|work= Financial Times |author=Crawford, Leslie Crawford |date=15 November 2007|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=16 November 2007 |url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071117205413/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21822492/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 17 November 2007}}</ref><ref name=Kingrow>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/7096950.stm Viewpoints: Chavez and King row.] BBC News, 16 November 2007. . Retrieved 17 November 2007.</ref>\n\nLess than 24 hours after the event, the king's words were used by sports commentators during the radio transmission of Spanish language football games to describe controversial events. A contest for the best audiovisual depiction of the event was announced in Spain.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://buscador.eluniversal.com/2007/11/13/cyt_ava_tono-de-la-frase-p_13A1191237.shtml|title=Tono de la frase \"\u00bfpor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" arrasa en politon\u00edas de celulares|work=[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]]|date=16 November 2007|accessdate=16 November 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924001929/http://buscador.eluniversal.com/2007/11/13/cyt_ava_tono-de-la-frase-p_13A1191237.shtml |archivedate=24 September 2009|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> ''[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]'' editorial page suggested that the phrase would have the power to change the course of history, as has been credited to [[Ronald Reagan]]'s, \"Mr. Gorbachev, [[tear down this wall!]]\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Royal message to petty dictator: Just shut up|last=Cooklis|first=Ray|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|location=Cincinnati, Ohio|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|page=8B|date=23 November 2007|accessdate=23 November 2007|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:CEQB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=11D5A7BEB47FB668&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB579A3BDA420|url-access=subscription |quote=History provides us with many examples of famous catch-phrases \u2013 the right words, uttered at just the right time \u2013 that have shown the power to change the course of events: ... Reagan's 'Mr. Gorbachev, tear down this wall.' Someday soon, we may be able to add to this list the blunt suggestion, already a hot Internet buzz-phrase and cell-phone ring tone, by an exasperated King Juan Carlos I to Venezuelan President Hugo Ch\u00e1vez during a recent summit in Chile: \"Why don't you shut up?\"|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026154535/http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004|archivedate=26 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}<!-- http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071123/EDIT01/711230358/1090/EDIT --></ref>\n\nThe ''Los Angeles Times'' said \"the Spanish-speaking world can hardly stop talking about [the incident]\", which provided \"fodder for satirists from Mexico City to Madrid\".<ref name=BattleRoyal /> The reaction was apparent \"in newspaper headlines, cable television and on YouTube. His phrase was reproduced on T-shirts, and cellphone ring tones. In Mexico City, the dust-up became a satirical skit, \"El Chabo del 8\".<!-- It's SATIRE, PARODY, not the real show! Please leave the typo! --> In El Salvador's capital, the phrase became a playful greeting\".<ref name=BattleRoyal>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-chavez17nov17,1,7510496.story?coll=la-headlines-world|title=King's words to Chavez start a battle royal|work=Los Angeles Times|author=Kraul, Chris|date=17 November 2007|accessdate=17 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206160526/http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-chavez17nov17,1,7510496.story?coll=la-headlines-world|archivedate=6 February 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In Australia ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' reported the king could earn a multimillion-euro business if he claimed rights over the phrase, which generated a ''[[Benny Hill Show]]''-style skit and a Nike ad, \"Juan do it. Just shut up\", with the Brazilian football star, [[Ronaldinho]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/world/why-dont-you-shut-up/2007/11/19/1195321697277.html|title=Royal outburst now a nasty little earner|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=20 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120215037/http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/why-dont-you-shut-up/2007/11/19/1195321697277.html|archivedate=20 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Canada's ''[[CBC News]]'' said an actor's voice was used to mimic the king's voice in the ringtone to avoid legal problems over the use of the phrase, which also generated sales of coffee mugs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/king-of-spain-tells-half-a-million-callers-to-shut-up-1.656819|title='King of Spain' tells half a million callers to 'shut up': New, insulting ringtone a smash hit in Spain|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122183800/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/king-of-spain-tells-half-a-million-callers-to-shut-up-1.656819|archivedate=22 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The infamous phrase was also referred to in a comic song called \"[[Baila el Chiki-chiki]]\", Spain's contribution to [[Eurovision 2008]], and in the song \"La Plata\", by the Brazilian band [[Jota Quest]].\n\nProtesters against the Ch\u00e1vez government adopted the phrase as their slogan;<ref name=Kingrow /> T-shirts in Venezuela had the slogan with the \"NO\" in capital letters, representing a call to vote against amendments in the [[2007 Venezuelan constitutional referendum|December 2007 constitutional referendum]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsvine.com/_news/2007/11/19/1108819-shut-up-is-hit-ringtone-in-spain|title=NBC News - Breaking News & Top Stories - Latest World, US & Local News|website=newsvine.com|accessdate=7 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026045539/http://www.newsvine.com/_news/2007/11/19/1108819-shut-up-is-hit-ringtone-in-spain|archivedate=26 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the phrase was used as a taunt when more than 100,000 marched in protest against Ch\u00e1vez's proposed constitutional changes.<ref name=\"MarchTaunt\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article2976631.ece|work=The Times|date=30 November 2007|title=100,000 march against Hugo Chavez reforms|accessdate=30 November 2007|location=London|first1=Hannah|last1=Strange|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080706165434/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article2976631.ece|archivedate=6 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn Argentina, a television program called ''Por qu\u00e9 no te callas'' began broadcasting on 6 December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laflecha.net/canales/comunicacion/noticias/el-por-que-no-te-callas-del-rey-juan-carlos-i-en-la-tv-argentina/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207183842/http://www.laflecha.net/canales/comunicacion/noticias/el-por-que-no-te-callas-del-rey-juan-carlos-i-en-la-tv-argentina|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 December 2007|title=El \"\u00bfpor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" del rey Juan Carlos I, en la TV argentina|work=La Flecha|date=5 December 2007|accessdate=12 January 2008|language=es}}</ref> The phrase was also seen at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://caracas.eluniversal.com/sudafrica10/2010/06/21/sur10_ava_frase-por-que-no-t_21A4063571.shtml |title=Frase \"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\" aparece en el Espa\u00f1a \u2013 Honduras |date=21 June 2010 |work=[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624101012/http://caracas.eluniversal.com/sudafrica10/2010/06/21/sur10_ava_frase-por-que-no-t_21A4063571.shtml |archivedate=24 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn Colombia, a famous YouTube animation called \"Vulgarcito\" depicted a summit between some Latin American countries and since Hugo Ch\u00e1vez never stopped talking in the animation, Vulgarcito, the main character, slapped him and shouted \"Shhh. It is time to quote the wise King of Spain and ask you: \u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JY06ySAnoKw|title=VULGARCITO vs CHAVEZ (original en HQ)|last=cardoto|date=16 December 2009|accessdate=7 May 2018|via=YouTube|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531231747/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JY06ySAnoKw|archivedate=31 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Alternative forms ==\nAccording to ''[[Foundation of Urgent Spanish|Fund\u00e9u BBVA]]'', the Urgent Spanish Foundation,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00a1Por qu\u00e9 no te callas!|url=http://www.fundeu.es/Consultas.aspx?frmOpcion=CONSULTA&frmFontSize=2&frmIdConsulta=690|work=Fund\u00e9u|accessdate=20 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216015604/http://www.fundeu.es/Consultas.aspx?frmOpcion=CONSULTA&frmFontSize=2&frmIdConsulta=690|archivedate=16 December 2009|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> and the Director of the [[Academia Chilena de la Lengua|Chilean Academy of the Spanish language]],<ref>{{cite web|title=En chileno la frase del rey Juan Carlos ser\u00eda: \u00a1por qu\u00e9 no te call\u00e1i vo!|url=http://www.lun.com/modulos/catalogo/paginas/2007/11/19/LUCPRDI02LU1911.htm?tipoPantalla=1024|work=[[Las \u00daltimas Noticias]]|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=20 November 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071121104137/http://www.lun.com/modulos/catalogo/paginas/2007/11/19/LUCPRDI02LU1911.htm?tipoPantalla=1024 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 21 November 2007|language=es}}</ref> the phrase uttered by the king, given the situation under which it was said, should be written with exclamation marks instead of question marks: ''\u00a1Por qu\u00e9 no te callas!'' Alternatively, it could be written using a combination of both exclamation and question marks: ''\u00a1\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?!'' or ''\u00bf\u00a1Por qu\u00e9 no te callas!?''\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Spain|Venezuela}}\n*[[Shut up]]\n*[[Spain\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{in lang|es}} [http://www.elpais.com/videos/ultimo/Rey/Chavez/callas/elpvid/20071110elpepuult_8/Ves/ El Rey a Ch\u00e1vez: \"\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 no te callas?\"] ''El Pa\u00eds'', 10 November 2007 (no subtitles)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X3Kzbo7tNLg Youtube video of the incident] (English subtitles)\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/11/18/AR2007111800945.html?hpid=opinionsbox1|title=Ch\u00e1vez and the King|author=Diehl, Jackson|work=The Washington Post|date=19 November 2007|accessdate=10 November 2007|page=A17}}\n\n{{Hugo Ch\u00e1vez}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Por Que No Te Callas}}\n[[Category:2007 in Chile]]\n[[Category:2007 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2007 in politics]]\n[[Category:2007 in Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic incidents]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic conferences in Chile]]\n[[Category:Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]]\n[[Category:International disputes]]\n[[Category:Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone culture]]\n[[Category:Political catchphrases]]\n[[Category:Political Internet memes]]\n[[Category:Spanish words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Spain\u2013Venezuela relations]]\n[[Category:Juan Carlos I of Spain]]\n[[Category:2007 in Spain]]\n[[Category:Political quotes]]\n[[Category:Words and phrases introduced in 2007]]\n", "name_user": "Opencooper", "label": "safe", "comment": "use template for non-English text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C2%BFPor_qu%C3%A9_no_te_callas%3F"}
