{"title_page": "Kim Hagdorn", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian cricketer and journalist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n'''Kim John Hagdorn''' (born 8 April 1955 in [[Subiaco, Western Australia]]) is a former [[first-class cricket]]er and Australian sports journalist flog. Kim embarrassed him self on live radio when he cried on air when discussing the westcoast eagles drug cheat willie Rioli\n\n==Cricket career==\nHagdorn was selected as a right-arm [[Seam bowling|medium-fast bowler]] and played the opening match for the [[Western Warriors|West Australian first-class cricket side]] in the 1977/78 [[Sheffield Shield]] season. He only bowled 6 overs for no wickets and did not get to bat as Western Australia beat Tasmania by an [[Result (cricket)#Statement of result|innings]] and 14 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/37/37579.html|title=The Home of CricketArchive|website=cricketarchive.com}}</ref>  He was replaced for the next match by [[Wayne Clark (cricketer)|Wayne Clark]] and was not selected again.\n\n==Journalism career==\nAfter his brief foray with the state cricket team, Hagdorn moved to sports journalism and became the chief [[Australian rules football]] writer for ''[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|The Sunday Times]]'' in Perth. He also appears on [[Triple M]] as a reporter for West Australian [[Australian Football League|AFL]] games and is a regular contributor to [[6PR]]'s football coverage.  He previously held a position as Communications Manager at the [[Western Australian Cricket Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/australia/content/story/117785.html|title=WACA announces two new appointments|website=ESPN Cricket Info|author=West Australian Cricket Association|date=June 13, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 he was awarded the [[Geoff Christian#Geoff Christian Media Award|Geoff Christian Media Award]] and the Jack Lee Best News Story Award by the WA Football Media Guild.\n\nIn 2008 he was again awarded the Jack Lee Award for Best Football News Story by the WA Football Media Guild.  In 2015 and 2016 he won both the best overall news story and best radio news story for his reports on [[Matt Priddis]]' injury (2015) and on [[Sam Mitchell (footballer)|Sam Mitchell]]'s move to the [[West Coast Eagles]] (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url= http://wafootball.com.au/news/9600/wafc-congratulates-football-media-award-winners|title=WAFC congratulates Football Media Award winners|date=11 November 2015|website=West Australian Football Commission}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://wafootball.com.au/news/11552/wafc-congratulates-football-media-award-winners|title=WAFC congratulates Football Media Award winners|date=9 November 2016|website=West Australian Football Commission}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Western Australia first-class cricketers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://content-www.cricinfo.com/australia/content/player/5784.html Cricinfo article on Kim Hagdorn]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hagdorn, Kim}}\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian rules football commentators]]\n[[Category:Australian sports journalists]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Western Australia cricketers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Perth, Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from Western Australia]]\n\n\n{{australia-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian cricketer and journalist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n'''Kim John Hagdorn''' (born 8 April 1955 in [[Subiaco, Western Australia]]) is a former [[first-class cricket]]er and Australian sports journalist.\n\n\n==Cricket career==\nHagdorn was selected as a right-arm [[Seam bowling|medium-fast bowler]] and played the opening match for the [[Western Warriors|West Australian first-class cricket side]] in the 1977/78 [[Sheffield Shield]] season. He only bowled 6 overs for no wickets and did not get to bat as Western Australia beat Tasmania by an [[Result (cricket)#Statement of result|innings]] and 14 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/37/37579.html|title=The Home of CricketArchive|website=cricketarchive.com}}</ref>  He was replaced for the next match by [[Wayne Clark (cricketer)|Wayne Clark]] and was not selected again.\n\n==Journalism career==\nAfter his brief foray with the state cricket team, Hagdorn moved to sports journalism and became the chief [[Australian rules football]] writer for ''[[The Sunday Times (Western Australia)|The Sunday Times]]'' in Perth. He also appears on [[Triple M]] as a reporter for West Australian [[Australian Football League|AFL]] games and is a regular contributor to [[6PR]]'s football coverage.  He previously held a position as Communications Manager at the [[Western Australian Cricket Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/australia/content/story/117785.html|title=WACA announces two new appointments|website=ESPN Cricket Info|author=West Australian Cricket Association|date=June 13, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 he was awarded the [[Geoff Christian#Geoff Christian Media Award|Geoff Christian Media Award]] and the Jack Lee Best News Story Award by the WA Football Media Guild.\n\nIn 2008 he was again awarded the Jack Lee Award for Best Football News Story by the WA Football Media Guild.  In 2015 and 2016 he won both the best overall news story and best radio news story for his reports on [[Matt Priddis]]' injury (2015) and on [[Sam Mitchell (footballer)|Sam Mitchell]]'s move to the [[West Coast Eagles]] (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url= http://wafootball.com.au/news/9600/wafc-congratulates-football-media-award-winners|title=WAFC congratulates Football Media Award winners|date=11 November 2015|website=West Australian Football Commission}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://wafootball.c