{"title_page": "Quintain (poetry)", "text_new": "A '''quintain''' or '''pentastich''' is any [[poetic]] form containing five lines.  Examples include the [[tanka]], the [[cinquain]], the [[Quintilla (poetry)|quintilla]] and the [[limerick (poetry)|limerick]].\n\n== Example ==\n[[File:Autumn Song, Dante Gabriel Rossetti.jpg|thumb|Original manuscript of \"Autumn Song\" by [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]], 1848, in the Ashley Library.]]\n <poem>\n       All, all a-lonely:\n\n  Three little children sitting on the sand,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  Three little children sitting in the sand,\n  All, all a-lonely\n  Down in  the green wood shady\u2015\n\n\u3000 There came an old woman, said Come on with me,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  There came an old women, said Come on with me,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  Down in the green wood shady\u2015\n\n\u3000 She stuck her pen-knife through their heart,\n\u3000 All, all a-lonely,\n  She stuck her pen-knife through their heart,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  Down in the green wood shady\u2015\n\n\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000--anonymous English Poem<ref>[[James Kirkup]], Hisatoshi Takata. ''What is English Poetry?'' Eichosha, 1970</ref>\n</poem>\n\n<poem>\n       Autumn Song\n\n Know'st thou not at the fall of the leaf \n How the heart feels a languid grief \n         Laid on it for a covering, \n         And how sleep seems a goodly thing \n In Autumn at the fall of the leaf? \n\n And how the swift beat of the brain \n Falters because it is in vain, \n         In Autumn at the fall of the leaf \n         Knowest thou not? and how the chief \n Of joys seems\u2014not to suffer pain? \n\n Know'st thou not at the fall of the leaf \n How the soul feels like a dried sheaf \n         Bound up at length for harvesting, \n         And how death seems a comely thing \n In Autumn at the fall of the leaf? \n\n                   --[[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]]<ref>[http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poem/174271 Autumn Song by Dante Gabriel Rossetti]</ref>\n\n</poem>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Mukhammas]]\n*[[Stanza]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | title=Metre, rhythm and verse form | url=https://archive.org/details/metrerhythmverse0000hobs | url-access=registration | series=The new critical idiom | first=Philip | last=Hobsbaum | publisher=Routledge | year=1996 | isbn=0-415-08797-X | pages=[https://archive.org/details/metrerhythmverse0000hobs/page/186 186\u2013188] }}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.thepoetsgarret.com/quintet.html Five Line Poetry Forms]\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Poetic forms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quintain(poetry)}}\n[[Category:Stanzaic form]]\n[[Category:Poetic form]]\n\n[[fr:Quintil]]\n[[ja:\u4e94\u884c\u9023]]\n", "text_old": "A '''quintain''' or '''pentastich''' is any [[poetic]] form containing five lines.  Examples include the [[tanka]], the [[cinquain]], and the [[limerick (poetry)|limerick]].\n\n== Example ==\n[[File:Autumn Song, Dante Gabriel Rossetti.jpg|thumb|Original manuscript of \"Autumn Song\" by [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]], 1848, in the Ashley Library.]]\n <poem>\n       All, all a-lonely:\n\n  Three little children sitting on the sand,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  Three little children sitting in the sand,\n  All, all a-lonely\n  Down in  the green wood shady\u2015\n\n\u3000 There came an old woman, said Come on with me,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  There came an old women, said Come on with me,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  Down in the green wood shady\u2015\n\n\u3000 She stuck her pen-knife through their heart,\n\u3000 All, all a-lonely,\n  She stuck her pen-knife through their heart,\n  All, all a-lonely,\n  Down in the green wood shady\u2015\n\n\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000\u3000--anonymous English Poem<ref>[[James Kirkup]], Hisatoshi Takata. ''What is English Poetry?'' Eichosha, 1970</ref>\n</poem>\n\n<poem>\n       Autumn Song\n\n Know'st thou not at the fall of the leaf \n How the heart feels a languid grief \n         Laid on it for a covering, \n         And how sleep seems a goodly thing \n In Autumn at the fall of the leaf? \n\n And how the swift beat of the brain \n Falters because it is in vain, \n         In Autumn at the fall of the leaf \n         Knowest thou not? and how the chief \n Of joys seems\u2014not to suffer pain? \n\n Know'st thou not at the fall of the leaf \n How the soul feels like a dried sheaf \n         Bound up at length for harvesting, \n         And how death seems a comely thing \n In Autumn at the fall of the leaf? \n\n                   --[[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]]<ref>[http://www.poetryfoundation.org/poem/174271 Autumn Song by Dante Gabriel Rossetti]</ref>\n\n</poem>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Mukhammas]]\n*[[Stanza]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | title=Metre, rhythm and verse form | url=https://archive.org/details/metrerhythmverse0000hobs | url-access=registration | series=The new critical idiom | first=Philip | last=Hobsbaum | publisher=Routledge | year=1996 | isbn=0-415-08797-X | pages=[https://archive.org/details/metrerhythmverse0000hobs/page/186 186\u2013188] }}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.thepoetsgarret.com/quintet.html Five Line Poetry Forms]\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{Poetic forms}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quintain(poetry)}}\n[[Category:Stanzaic form]]\n[[Category:Poetic form]]\n\n[[fr:Quintil]]\n[[ja:\u4e94\u884c\u9023]]\n", "name_user": "Srnec", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintain_(poetry)"}
{"title_page": "Gender essentialism", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n  {{Essay-like |reason=essay-like throughout, but as one example: 'Disrupting gender essentialism' is not a NPOV section title, it's a thesis, opinion, or call to arms |date=December 2017}}\n  {{Technical |date=December 2017}}\n  {{Inadequate lead|date=December 2017}}\n  {{Globalize |reason=more attention needed to non-European and non-Western societies|date=December 2017}}\n  {{POV|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n\n'''Gender essentialism''' is a concept used to examine the attribution of fixed, intrinsic, innate qualities to women and men.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Gender and Psychological Essentialism|journal = Enfance; Psychologie, Pedagogie, Neuropsychiatrie, Sociologie|volume = 58|issue = 3|pages = 293\u2013310|pmc = 3082140|year = 2006|last1 = Heyman|first1 = G. D.|last2 = Giles|first2 = J. W.|pmid = 21528097}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Declaration|last=|first=|citeseerx = 10.1.1.871.3140|year = 2010}}</ref> In this theory, there are certain universal, innate, biologically- or psychologically-based features of [[gender]] that are at the root of observed differences in the behavior of men and women.<ref name=\"Hepburn-2008\">{{cite book | last = Hepburn | first = Alexa | chapter = Feminist critics: hetrosexism and lesbian and gay psychology |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rfIFQIa9rFMC&pg=PA107 | title = An introduction to critical social psychology | page = 107 | publisher = Sage | location = London Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780761962106 }}</ref> In Western civilization, it is suggested in writings going back to [[ancient Greece]].<ref name=\"Bem-1993\">{{cite book | last = Bem | first = Sandra | authorlink = Sandra Bem | chapter = Introduction | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=u2a59A74CPcC&pg=PA1 | title = The lenses of gender: transforming the debate on sexual inequality | pages = [https://archive.org/details/lensesofgender00sand/page/1 1&ndash;2] | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven, Connecticut | year = 1993 | isbn = 9780300061635 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/lensesofgender00sand/page/1 }}</ref>{{rp|1}} With the advent of [[Christianity]], the earlier Greek model was expressed in theological discussions as the doctrine that there are two distinct sexes, male and female created by God, and that individuals are immutably one or the other.<ref name=\"Thatcher-2011\">{{cite book | last = Thatcher | first = Adrian | chapter = Gender: language, power, and history |chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=hcNyAOxMLFsC&pg=PA19 | title = God, sex, and gender: an introduction |page=19 | publisher = Wiley-Blackwell | location = Chichester, West Sussex, United Kingdom | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781444396379 }}</ref> This view remained essentially unchanged until the middle of the 19th century.<ref name=\"Bem-1993\" /> This changed the locus of the origin of the essential differences, in [[Sandra Bem]]'s words, \"from God's grand creation [to] its scientific equivalent: evolution's grand creation,\" but the belief in an immutable origin had not changed.<ref name=\"Bem-1993\" />{{rp|2}}\n\nAlternatives to gender essentialism were proposed in the mid-20th century. During [[second-wave feminism]], [[Simone de Beauvoir]] and other feminists in the 1960s and 70s theorized that gender differences were [[social construction of gender|socially constructed]]. In other words, people gradually conform to gender differences through their experience of the social world. More recently, [[Judith Butler]] theorized that [[performativity|people construct gender by performing\u00a0it]].\n\n== Okay Dave ==\nOkay [[The Rubbish World of Dave Spud|Dave Spud]]\n\n== Manifestations ==\n\n=== In feminism ===\n\nIn [[feminist theory]] and [[gender studies]], '''gender essentialism''' is the attribution of a fixed essence to women.<ref name=\":03\">{{cite book | last = Grosz | first = Elizabeth A. | author-link = Elizabeth Grosz | title = Space, time, and perversion: essays on the politics of bodies | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 1995 | url = https://books.google.com/books/about/Space_Time_and_Perversion.html?id=Htf7y-rcVFwC | isbn = 9780415911368 }}</ref> Women's essence is assumed to be universal and is generally identified with those characteristics viewed as being specifically feminine.<ref name=\":03\" /> These ideas of femininity are usually related to biology and often concern psychological characteristics such as nurturance, empathy, support, non-competitiveness, etc.<ref name=\":03\" /> Feminist theorist [[Elizabeth Grosz]] states in her 1995 publication, ''Space, Time and Perversion: Essays on the Politics of Bodies'', that essentialism \"entails the belief that those characteristics defined as women's essence are shared in common by all women at all times. It implies a limit of the variations and possibilities of change\u2014it is not possible for a subject to act in a manner contrary to her essence. Her essence underlies all the apparent variations differentiating women from each other. Essentialism thus refers to the existence of fixed characteristic, given attributes, and ahistorical functions that limit the possibilities of change and thus of social reorganization.\"<ref name=\":03\" />\n\nFurthermore, biologism is a particular form of essentialism that defines women's essence in terms of biological capacities.<ref name=\":03\" /> This form of essentialism is based on a form of reductionism, meaning that social and cultural factors are the effects of biological causes.<ref name=\":03\" /> Biological reductivism \"claim[s] that anatomical and physiological differences\u2014especially reproductive differences\u2014characteristic of human males and females determine both the meaning of masculinity and femininity and the appropriately different positions of men and women in society\".<ref name=\":43\">{{cite journal | last = Diquinzio | first = Patrice | title = Exclusion and essentialism in feminist theory: the problem of mothering | journal = [[Hypatia (journal)|Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy]] | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = 1&ndash;20 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1527-2001.1993.tb00033.x | jstor = 3810402 | date = Summer 1993 | ref = harv }}</ref> Biologism uses the functions of reproduction, nurturance, neurology, neurophysiology, and endocrinology to limit women's social and psychological possibilities according to biologically established limits.<ref name=\":03\" /> It asserts the science of biology to constitute an unalterable definition of identity, which inevitably \"amounts to a permanent form of social containment for women\".<ref name=\":03\" /> Naturalism is also a part of the system of essentialism where a fixed nature is postulated for women through the means of theological or ontological rather than biological grounds. An example of this would be the claim that women's nature is a God-given attribute, or the ontological invariants in [[Existentialism|Sartrean existentialism]] or [[Sigmund Freud|Freudian psychoanalysis]] that distinguish the sexes in the \"claim that the human subject is somehow free or that the subjects social position is a function of his or her genital morphology\".<ref name=\":03\" /> These systems are used to homogenize women into one singular category and to strengthen a binary between men and women.<ref name=\":03\" />\n\n=== In religion ===\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\n==== LDS ====\n\nThe official view of [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (Mormons; LDS) is an essentialist belief in gender.  The 1995 LDS statement, [[The Family: A Proclamation to the World]] states the official view, and declares gender to be an \"essential characteristic\" of sons and daughters of God, and an \"eternal identity.\"  Mormon people generally believe in an eternal life, and that it would be impossible for one's eternal gender to be different from one's physical, birth sex.  Church regulations permit, but don't mandate, [[ex-communication]] for those who choose [[sexual reassignment surgery]], and deny them membership in the [[priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood]].<ref name=\"Copeland-2015\">{{cite book |last1=Copeland |first1=Mychal  |last2=Rose |first2=D\u2019vorah |last3=Gustav-Wrathall |first3=John |chapter=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (Mormon) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=D7XQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31 | title = Struggling in good faith: LGBTQI inclusion from 13 American religious perspectives |page=31| publisher = Walking Together, Finding the Way/SkyLight Paths Publishing | location = Woodstock, Vermont | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781594736025 }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and alternative theories of gender ==\n{{Cleanup rewrite|the section is full of jargon; there are other articles better suited for this information, this should just summarize the topic. |section |date=December 2017}}\n\n=== Social construction of gender ===\n\n{{Main|Social construction of gender}}\nThe main alternative to gender essentialism is the theory of the [[social construction of gender]].  In contrast to gender essentialism, which views differences between men and women as innate, universal, and immutable, social constructionism views gender as created and influenced by society and culture, which differ according to time and place, with roles societally defined as appropriate for a person of a given sex becoming the standard against which members of that sex are measured. Theories of the social construction of gender grew out of theories in [[second-wave feminism]] in the latter half of the 20th century.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==== Gender performativity ====\n\n{{Main|Gender performativity}}\n[[Judith Butler]]'s theory of [[gender performativity]] can be seen as a means to show \"the ways in which reified and naturalized conceptions of gender might be understood as constituted and, hence, capable of being constituted differently\".<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal | last = Butler | first = Judith | author-link = Judith Butler | title = Performative acts and gender constitution: an essay in phenomenology and feminist theory | journal = [[Theatre Journal]] | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 519&ndash;531 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/3207893 | jstor = 3207893 | date = December 1988 | ref = harv }} [http://seas3.elte.hu/coursematerial/TimarAndrea/17a.Butler,performative%5B1%5D.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Butler uses the phenomenological theory of acts espoused by [[Edmund Husserl]], [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]] and [[George Herbert Mead]], which seeks to explain the mundane way in which \"social agents constitute social reality through language, gesture, and all manner of symbolic social sign\", to create her conception of gender performativity.<ref name=\":13\" /> She begins by quoting [[Simone de Beauvoir|Simone de Beauvoir's]] claim: <blockquote href=\"Parmenides (dialogue)\">''\"...one is not born, but, rather, becomes a woman.\"''<ref>{{cite book | last = de Beauvoir | first = Simone | author-link = Simone de Beauvoir | title = The second sex | publisher = Vintage Classic | location = London | year = 2015 | origyear = 1949 | isbn = 9781784870386 }}</ref> </blockquote>This statement distinguishes sex from gender suggesting that gender is an aspect of identity that is gradually acquired.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite journal | last = Butler | first = Judith | author-link = Judith Butler | title = Sex and gender in Simone de Beauvoir's ''Second Sex'' | journal = Yale French Studies| volume = | issue = 72 | pages = 35&ndash;49 | publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/2930225 | jstor = 2930225 | date = 1986 | ref = harv }}</ref> This distinction between sex, as the anatomical aspects of the female body, and gender, as the cultural meaning that forms the body and the various modes of bodily articulation, means that it is \"no longer possible to attribute the values or social functions of women to biological necessity\".<ref name=\":23\" /> Butler interprets this claim as an appropriation of the doctrine of constituting acts from the tradition of phenomenology.<ref name=\":13\" /> Butler concludes that \"gender is in no way a stable identity or locus of agency from which various acts proceed; rather, it is an identity tenuously constituted in time\u2014an identity instituted through the stylization of the body and, hence, must be understood as the mundane way in which bodily gestures, movements and enactments of various kinds constitute the illusion of an abiding gendered self\".<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nCandace West and Sarah Fenstermaker also conceptualize gender \"as a routine, methodical, and ongoing accomplishment, which involves a complex of perceptual, interactional and micropolitical activities that cast particular pursuits as expressions of manly and womanly 'natures'\" in their 1995 text ''Doing Difference''.<ref name=\":53\">{{cite journal | last1 = West | first1 = Candace | last2 = Fenstermaker | first2 = Sarah | title = Doing difference | journal = [[Gender & Society]] | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 8&ndash;37 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/089124395009001002 | jstor = 189596 | date =  February 1995 | ref = harv |url=http://www.csun.edu/~snk1966/Doing%20Difference.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThis does not mean that the material nature of the human body is denied, instead, it is re-comprehended as separate from the process by which \"the body comes to bear cultural meanings\".<ref name=\":13\" /> Therefore, the essence of gender is not natural because gender itself is not a natural fact<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":23\" /> but the outcome of the sedimentation of specific corporeal acts that have been inscribed through repetition and rearticulation over time onto the body.<ref name=\":13\" /> \"If the reality of gender is constituted by the performance itself, then there is no recourse to an essential and unrealized 'sex' or 'gender' which gender performances ostensibly express\".<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n==== Intersectionality ====\n\n{{Main|Intersectionality}}\n{{One source|section|date=October 2017}}\nAnalyzing gender has been a concern of feminist theory. There have been many modes of understanding how gender addresses meaning,<ref name=\":43\" /> but developing such theories of gender can obscure the significance of other aspects of women's identities, such as race, class, and sexual orientation, which marginalizes the experiences and voices of women of colour, non-Western women, working-class women, queer women, and trans women.<ref name=\":43\" /> As a challenge to feminist theory, essentialism refers to the problem of theorizing gender as both an identity and a mark of difference. This refers to a problem for the concept of subjectivity presupposed by feminist theories of gender.<ref name=\":43\" /> There are arguments primarily by black and lesbian feminists that feminist theory has capitalized on the idea of gender essentialism by using the category of gender to appeal to \"women's experience\" as a whole.<ref name=\":43\" /> By doing this, feminist theory makes universalizing and normalizing claims for and about women, which are only true of white, Western, heterosexual, [[cisgender]], middle- or upper-class women,<ref name=\":43\" /> but which it implies are situations, perspectives and experiences true of all women. Patrice DiQuinzio discusses \"how critics of exclusion see this as a function of feminist theory's commitment to theorizing gender exclusively and articulating women's experiences in terms of gender alone\".<ref name=\":43\" /> Instead one must theorize feminism in a way that takes the interlocking category of experiences between race, class, gender, and sexuality into consideration; an [[Intersectionality|intersectional]] model of thinking.<ref name=\":53\" />\n\n===== Mothering =====\n\nSome feminists, such as DiQuinzio and [[Nancy Chodorow]], have used the idea of a woman's essence to link gender socialization with exclusively female mothering.<ref name=\":43\" /> Butler disagreed, because not all women are mothers, due to age or personal choice, and even some mothers do not regard motherhood as the most important aspect of political struggle.<ref name=\":33\" />\n\n===== Transfeminism =====\n\n{{Main|Transfeminism}}\nFurthermore, the essentialism of gender in feminist theory presents a problem when understanding transfeminism. Instead of understanding trans studies as another subsection or subjectivity to be subsumed under the category of \"woman\", we understand the task of trans studies to be \"the breaking apart of this category, particularly if that breaking requires a new articulation of the relation between sex and gender, male and female\".<ref name=\":63\">{{cite book | last = Salamon | first = Gayle | chapter = Transfeminism and the future of gender | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vEDoLJvklZAC&pg=PA115 | editor-last = Scott| editor-first = Joan Wallach | editor-link = Joan Wallach Scott | title = Women's studies on the edge | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2008 | isbn = 9780822389101 }}</ref> Trans subjectivity challenges the binary of gender essentialism as it disrupts the \"fixed taxonomies of gender\" and this creates a resistance in women's studies, which as a discipline has historically depended upon the fixedness of gender.<ref name=\":63\" /> Trans identities break down the very possibility of gender essentialism by queering the binary of gender, gender roles and expectations.<ref>{{Cite news|last = Jakubowski|first = Kaylee|url = http://everydayfeminism.com/2015/03/trans-people-gender-essentialism/|title = No, the existence of trans people doesn't validate gender essentialism|work = Everyday Feminism|date = March 9, 2015 | access-date = May 28, 2017 }}</ref> In recent years, through the work of transfeminists such as [[Sandy Stone (artist)|Sandy Stone]], the theory of trans women and their inclusion into feminist spaces has opened, just as theories of race, class, sexuality and ability did.\n\n==== Child development ====\nSocial categories such as gender are often essentialized by not only adults but children, as young children have been shown to display essentialist beliefs about gender preferences and indications.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Meyer | first1 = Meredith | last2 = Gelman | first2 = Susan A. | title = Gender essentialism in children and parents: implications for the development of gender stereotyping and gender-typed preferences | journal = [[Sex Roles (journal)|Sex Roles]] | volume = 75 | issue = 9&ndash;10 | pages = 409&ndash;421 | publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] | doi = 10.1007/s11199-016-0646-6 | date = November 2016 | ref = harv }}</ref> Proponents of gender essentialism propose that children from the age of 4 to 10 show the tendency to endorse the role of nature in determining gender-stereotyped properties, an \"early bias to view gender categories as predictive of essential\", which gradually declines as they pass elementary school years.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Taylor | first = Morgan G. | title = The development of children's beliefs about social and biological aspects of gender differences | journal = [[Child Development (journal)|Child Development]] | volume = 67 | issue = 4 | pages = 1555&ndash;1571 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-8624.1996.tb01814.x | pmid = 8890500 | date = August 1996 | ref = harv }}</ref> Another indicator of gender essentialism in child development is how they begin to employ essentialist manifestation as a tool for reasoning and perceiving gender stereotyping from as young as 24 months.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Poulin-Dubois | first1 = Diane | last2 = Serbin | first2 = Lisa A. | last3 = Eichstedt | first3 = Julie A. | last4 = Sen | first4 = Maya G. | last5 = Beissel | first5 = Clara F. | title = Men don't put on make-up: toddlers' knowledge of the gender stereotyping of household activities | journal = Social Development | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 166&ndash;181 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/1467-9507.00193 | date = May 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n=== Post-structuralism ===\n\n{{Main|Post-structuralism}}\n{{One source|section|date=October 2017}}\n\n[[Poststructuralism]] indicates \"a field of critical practices that cannot be totalized and that, therefore, interrogate the formative and exclusionary power of sexual difference\", says Butler.<ref name=\":33\">{{cite book | last = Butler | first = Judith|last2 = Wallach Scott|first2 = Joan | author-link1 = Judith Butler | author-link2 = Joan Wallach Scott | title = Feminists theorize the political | publisher = Routledge | location = New York Oxfordshire, England | year = 1992 | isbn = 9780203723999 }}</ref> Therefore, through the poststructuralist lens, the critique of gender essentialism is possible because poststructuralist theory generates analyses, critiques, and political interventions, and opens up a political imaginary for feminism that is otherwise constrained.<ref name=\":33\" /> Feminist poststructuralism does not designate a position from which one operates, but offers a set of tools and terms to be \"reused and rethought, exposed as strategic instruments and effects, and subjected to a critical reinscription and redeployment\".<ref name=\":33\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Empathizing\u2013systemizing theory]]\n* [[Essentialism]]\n* [[French post-structuralist feminism]]\n* [[Gendered sexuality]]\n* [[Neuroscience of sex differences]]\n* [[Neuroplasticity]]\n* [[The NeuroGenderings Network]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Rippon | first1 = Gina | last2 = Jordan-Young | first2 = Rebecca | last3 = Fine | first3 = Cordelia | last4 = Kaiser | first4 = Anelis | author-link1 = Gina Rippon | author-link2 = Rebecca Jordan-Young | author-link3 = Cordelia Fine | author-link4 = Anelis Kaiser | title = Recommendations for sex/gender neuroimaging research: key principles and implications for research design, analysis and interpretation | journal = Frontiers in Human Neuroscience | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 650 | publisher = [[Frontiers Media|Frontiers]] | doi = 10.3389/fnhum.2014.00650 | pmid = 25221493 | pmc = 4147717 | date = 28 August 2014 | ref = harv }}\n\n[[Category:Feminist terminology]]\n[[Category:Feminist theory]]\n[[Category:Social constructionism]]\n[[Category:Essentialism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n  {{Essay-like |reason=essay-like throughout, but as one example: 'Disrupting gender essentialism' is not a NPOV section title, it's a thesis, opinion, or call to arms |date=December 2017}}\n  {{Technical |date=December 2017}}\n  {{Inadequate lead|date=December 2017}}\n  {{Globalize |reason=more attention needed to non-European and non-Western societies|date=December 2017}}\n  {{POV|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n\n'''Gender essentialism''' is a concept used to examine the attribution of fixed, intrinsic, innate qualities to women and men.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Gender and Psychological Essentialism|journal = Enfance; Psychologie, Pedagogie, Neuropsychiatrie, Sociologie|volume = 58|issue = 3|pages = 293\u2013310|pmc = 3082140|year = 2006|last1 = Heyman|first1 = G. D.|last2 = Giles|first2 = J. W.|pmid = 21528097}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Declaration|last=|first=|citeseerx = 10.1.1.871.3140|year = 2010}}</ref> In this theory, there are certain universal, innate, biologically- or psychologically-based features of [[gender]] that are at the root of observed differences in the behavior of men and women.<ref name=\"Hepburn-2008\">{{cite book | last = Hepburn | first = Alexa | chapter = Feminist critics: hetrosexism and lesbian and gay psychology |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=rfIFQIa9rFMC&pg=PA107 | title = An introduction to critical social psychology | page = 107 | publisher = Sage | location = London Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780761962106 }}</ref> In Western civilization, it is suggested in writings going back to [[ancient Greece]].<ref name=\"Bem-1993\">{{cite book | last = Bem | first = Sandra | authorlink = Sandra Bem | chapter = Introduction | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=u2a59A74CPcC&pg=PA1 | title = The lenses of gender: transforming the debate on sexual inequality | pages = [https://archive.org/details/lensesofgender00sand/page/1 1&ndash;2] | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven, Connecticut | year = 1993 | isbn = 9780300061635 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/lensesofgender00sand/page/1 }}</ref>{{rp|1}} With the advent of [[Christianity]], the earlier Greek model was expressed in theological discussions as the doctrine that there are two distinct sexes, male and female created by God, and that individuals are immutably one or the other.<ref name=\"Thatcher-2011\">{{cite book | last = Thatcher | first = Adrian | chapter = Gender: language, power, and history |chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=hcNyAOxMLFsC&pg=PA19 | title = God, sex, and gender: an introduction |page=19 | publisher = Wiley-Blackwell | location = Chichester, West Sussex, United Kingdom | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781444396379 }}</ref> This view remained essentially unchanged until the middle of the 19th century.<ref name=\"Bem-1993\" /> This changed the locus of the origin of the essential differences, in [[Sandra Bem]]'s words, \"from God's grand creation [to] its scientific equivalent: evolution's grand creation,\" but the belief in an immutable origin had not changed.<ref name=\"Bem-1993\" />{{rp|2}}\n\nAlternatives to gender essentialism were proposed in the mid-20th century. During [[second-wave feminism]], [[Simone de Beauvoir]] and other feminists in the 1960s and 70s theorized that gender differences were [[social construction of gender|socially constructed]]. In other words, people gradually conform to gender differences through their experience of the social world. More recently, [[Judith Butler]] theorized that [[performativity|people construct gender by performing\u00a0it]].\n\n== Manifestations ==\n\n=== In feminism ===\n\nIn [[feminist theory]] and [[gender studies]], '''gender essentialism''' is the attribution of a fixed essence to women.<ref name=\":03\">{{cite book | last = Grosz | first = Elizabeth A. | author-link = Elizabeth Grosz | title = Space, time, and perversion: essays on the politics of bodies | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 1995 | url = https://books.google.com/books/about/Space_Time_and_Perversion.html?id=Htf7y-rcVFwC | isbn = 9780415911368 }}</ref> Women's essence is assumed to be universal and is generally identified with those characteristics viewed as being specifically feminine.<ref name=\":03\" /> These ideas of femininity are usually related to biology and often concern psychological characteristics such as nurturance, empathy, support, non-competitiveness, etc.<ref name=\":03\" /> Feminist theorist [[Elizabeth Grosz]] states in her 1995 publication, ''Space, Time and Perversion: Essays on the Politics of Bodies'', that essentialism \"entails the belief that those characteristics defined as women's essence are shared in common by all women at all times. It implies a limit of the variations and possibilities of change\u2014it is not possible for a subject to act in a manner contrary to her essence. Her essence underlies all the apparent variations differentiating women from each other. Essentialism thus refers to the existence of fixed characteristic, given attributes, and ahistorical functions that limit the possibilities of change and thus of social reorganization.\"<ref name=\":03\" />\n\nFurthermore, biologism is a particular form of essentialism that defines women's essence in terms of biological capacities.<ref name=\":03\" /> This form of essentialism is based on a form of reductionism, meaning that social and cultural factors are the effects of biological causes.<ref name=\":03\" /> Biological reductivism \"claim[s] that anatomical and physiological differences\u2014especially reproductive differences\u2014characteristic of human males and females determine both the meaning of masculinity and femininity and the appropriately different positions of men and women in society\".<ref name=\":43\">{{cite journal | last = Diquinzio | first = Patrice | title = Exclusion and essentialism in feminist theory: the problem of mothering | journal = [[Hypatia (journal)|Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy]] | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = 1&ndash;20 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1527-2001.1993.tb00033.x | jstor = 3810402 | date = Summer 1993 | ref = harv }}</ref> Biologism uses the functions of reproduction, nurturance, neurology, neurophysiology, and endocrinology to limit women's social and psychological possibilities according to biologically established limits.<ref name=\":03\" /> It asserts the science of biology to constitute an unalterable definition of identity, which inevitably \"amounts to a permanent form of social containment for women\".<ref name=\":03\" /> Naturalism is also a part of the system of essentialism where a fixed nature is postulated for women through the means of theological or ontological rather than biological grounds. An example of this would be the claim that women's nature is a God-given attribute, or the ontological invariants in [[Existentialism|Sartrean existentialism]] or [[Sigmund Freud|Freudian psychoanalysis]] that distinguish the sexes in the \"claim that the human subject is somehow free or that the subjects social position is a function of his or her genital morphology\".<ref name=\":03\" /> These systems are used to homogenize women into one singular category and to strengthen a binary between men and women.<ref name=\":03\" />\n\n=== In religion ===\n{{expand section|date=March 2020}}\n==== LDS ====\n\nThe official view of [[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (Mormons; LDS) is an essentialist belief in gender.  The 1995 LDS statement, [[The Family: A Proclamation to the World]] states the official view, and declares gender to be an \"essential characteristic\" of sons and daughters of God, and an \"eternal identity.\"  Mormon people generally believe in an eternal life, and that it would be impossible for one's eternal gender to be different from one's physical, birth sex.  Church regulations permit, but don't mandate, [[ex-communication]] for those who choose [[sexual reassignment surgery]], and deny them membership in the [[priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|priesthood]].<ref name=\"Copeland-2015\">{{cite book |last1=Copeland |first1=Mychal  |last2=Rose |first2=D\u2019vorah |last3=Gustav-Wrathall |first3=John |chapter=The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (Mormon) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=D7XQCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31 | title = Struggling in good faith: LGBTQI inclusion from 13 American religious perspectives |page=31| publisher = Walking Together, Finding the Way/SkyLight Paths Publishing | location = Woodstock, Vermont | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781594736025 }}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and alternative theories of gender ==\n{{Cleanup rewrite|the section is full of jargon; there are other articles better suited for this information, this should just summarize the topic. |section |date=December 2017}}\n\n=== Social construction of gender ===\n\n{{Main|Social construction of gender}}\nThe main alternative to gender essentialism is the theory of the [[social construction of gender]].  In contrast to gender essentialism, which views differences between men and women as innate, universal, and immutable, social constructionism views gender as created and influenced by society and culture, which differ according to time and place, with roles societally defined as appropriate for a person of a given sex becoming the standard against which members of that sex are measured. Theories of the social construction of gender grew out of theories in [[second-wave feminism]] in the latter half of the 20th century.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==== Gender performativity ====\n\n{{Main|Gender performativity}}\n[[Judith Butler]]'s theory of [[gender performativity]] can be seen as a means to show \"the ways in which reified and naturalized conceptions of gender might be understood as constituted and, hence, capable of being constituted differently\".<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal | last = Butler | first = Judith | author-link = Judith Butler | title = Performative acts and gender constitution: an essay in phenomenology and feminist theory | journal = [[Theatre Journal]] | volume = 40 | issue = 4 | pages = 519&ndash;531 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/3207893 | jstor = 3207893 | date = December 1988 | ref = harv }} [http://seas3.elte.hu/coursematerial/TimarAndrea/17a.Butler,performative%5B1%5D.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Butler uses the phenomenological theory of acts espoused by [[Edmund Husserl]], [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]] and [[George Herbert Mead]], which seeks to explain the mundane way in which \"social agents constitute social reality through language, gesture, and all manner of symbolic social sign\", to create her conception of gender performativity.<ref name=\":13\" /> She begins by quoting [[Simone de Beauvoir|Simone de Beauvoir's]] claim: <blockquote href=\"Parmenides (dialogue)\">''\"...one is not born, but, rather, becomes a woman.\"''<ref>{{cite book | last = de Beauvoir | first = Simone | author-link = Simone de Beauvoir | title = The second sex | publisher = Vintage Classic | location = London | year = 2015 | origyear = 1949 | isbn = 9781784870386 }}</ref> </blockquote>This statement distinguishes sex from gender suggesting that gender is an aspect of identity that is gradually acquired.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite journal | last = Butler | first = Judith | author-link = Judith Butler | title = Sex and gender in Simone de Beauvoir's ''Second Sex'' | journal = Yale French Studies| volume = | issue = 72 | pages = 35&ndash;49 | publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/2930225 | jstor = 2930225 | date = 1986 | ref = harv }}</ref> This distinction between sex, as the anatomical aspects of the female body, and gender, as the cultural meaning that forms the body and the various modes of bodily articulation, means that it is \"no longer possible to attribute the values or social functions of women to biological necessity\".<ref name=\":23\" /> Butler interprets this claim as an appropriation of the doctrine of constituting acts from the tradition of phenomenology.<ref name=\":13\" /> Butler concludes that \"gender is in no way a stable identity or locus of agency from which various acts proceed; rather, it is an identity tenuously constituted in time\u2014an identity instituted through the stylization of the body and, hence, must be understood as the mundane way in which bodily gestures, movements and enactments of various kinds constitute the illusion of an abiding gendered self\".<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nCandace West and Sarah Fenstermaker also conceptualize gender \"as a routine, methodical, and ongoing accomplishment, which involves a complex of perceptual, interactional and micropolitical activities that cast particular pursuits as expressions of manly and womanly 'natures'\" in their 1995 text ''Doing Difference''.<ref name=\":53\">{{cite journal | last1 = West | first1 = Candace | last2 = Fenstermaker | first2 = Sarah | title = Doing difference | journal = [[Gender & Society]] | volume = 9 | issue = 1 | pages = 8&ndash;37 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/089124395009001002 | jstor = 189596 | date =  February 1995 | ref = harv |url=http://www.csun.edu/~snk1966/Doing%20Difference.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThis does not mean that the material nature of the human body is denied, instead, it is re-comprehended as separate from the process by which \"the body comes to bear cultural meanings\".<ref name=\":13\" /> Therefore, the essence of gender is not natural because gender itself is not a natural fact<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":23\" /> but the outcome of the sedimentation of specific corporeal acts that have been inscribed through repetition and rearticulation over time onto the body.<ref name=\":13\" /> \"If the reality of gender is constituted by the performance itself, then there is no recourse to an essential and unrealized 'sex' or 'gender' which gender performances ostensibly express\".<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n==== Intersectionality ====\n\n{{Main|Intersectionality}}\n{{One source|section|date=October 2017}}\nAnalyzing gender has been a concern of feminist theory. There have been many modes of understanding how gender addresses meaning,<ref name=\":43\" /> but developing such theories of gender can obscure the significance of other aspects of women's identities, such as race, class, and sexual orientation, which marginalizes the experiences and voices of women of colour, non-Western women, working-class women, queer women, and trans women.<ref name=\":43\" /> As a challenge to feminist theory, essentialism refers to the problem of theorizing gender as both an identity and a mark of difference. This refers to a problem for the concept of subjectivity presupposed by feminist theories of gender.<ref name=\":43\" /> There are arguments primarily by black and lesbian feminists that feminist theory has capitalized on the idea of gender essentialism by using the category of gender to appeal to \"women's experience\" as a whole.<ref name=\":43\" /> By doing this, feminist theory makes universalizing and normalizing claims for and about women, which are only true of white, Western, heterosexual, [[cisgender]], middle- or upper-class women,<ref name=\":43\" /> but which it implies are situations, perspectives and experiences true of all women. Patrice DiQuinzio discusses \"how critics of exclusion see this as a function of feminist theory's commitment to theorizing gender exclusively and articulating women's experiences in terms of gender alone\".<ref name=\":43\" /> Instead one must theorize feminism in a way that takes the interlocking category of experiences between race, class, gender, and sexuality into consideration; an [[Intersectionality|intersectional]] model of thinking.<ref name=\":53\" />\n\n===== Mothering =====\n\nSome feminists, such as DiQuinzio and [[Nancy Chodorow]], have used the idea of a woman's essence to link gender socialization with exclusively female mothering.<ref name=\":43\" /> Butler disagreed, because not all women are mothers, due to age or personal choice, and even some mothers do not regard motherhood as the most important aspect of political struggle.<ref name=\":33\" />\n\n===== Transfeminism =====\n\n{{Main|Transfeminism}}\nFurthermore, the essentialism of gender in feminist theory presents a problem when understanding transfeminism. Instead of understanding trans studies as another subsection or subjectivity to be subsumed under the category of \"woman\", we understand the task of trans studies to be \"the breaking apart of this category, particularly if that breaking requires a new articulation of the relation between sex and gender, male and female\".<ref name=\":63\">{{cite book | last = Salamon | first = Gayle | chapter = Transfeminism and the future of gender | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vEDoLJvklZAC&pg=PA115 | editor-last = Scott| editor-first = Joan Wallach | editor-link = Joan Wallach Scott | title = Women's studies on the edge | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2008 | isbn = 9780822389101 }}</ref> Trans subjectivity challenges the binary of gender essentialism as it disrupts the \"fixed taxonomies of gender\" and this creates a resistance in women's studies, which as a discipline has historically depended upon the fixedness of gender.<ref name=\":63\" /> Trans identities break down the very possibility of gender essentialism by queering the binary of gender, gender roles and expectations.<ref>{{Cite news|last = Jakubowski|first = Kaylee|url = http://everydayfeminism.com/2015/03/trans-people-gender-essentialism/|title = No, the existence of trans people doesn't validate gender essentialism|work = Everyday Feminism|date = March 9, 2015 | access-date = May 28, 2017 }}</ref> In recent years, through the work of transfeminists such as [[Sandy Stone (artist)|Sandy Stone]], the theory of trans women and their inclusion into feminist spaces has opened, just as theories of race, class, sexuality and ability did.\n\n==== Child development ====\nSocial categories such as gender are often essentialized by not only adults but children, as young children have been shown to display essentialist beliefs about gender preferences and indications.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Meyer | first1 = Meredith | last2 = Gelman | first2 = Susan A. | title = Gender essentialism in children and parents: implications for the development of gender stereotyping and gender-typed preferences | journal = [[Sex Roles (journal)|Sex Roles]] | volume = 75 | issue = 9&ndash;10 | pages = 409&ndash;421 | publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] | doi = 10.1007/s11199-016-0646-6 | date = November 2016 | ref = harv }}</ref> Proponents of gender essentialism propose that children from the age of 4 to 10 show the tendency to endorse the role of nature in determining gender-stereotyped properties, an \"early bias to view gender categories as predictive of essential\", which gradually declines as they pass elementary school years.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Taylor | first = Morgan G. | title = The development of children's beliefs about social and biological aspects of gender differences | journal = [[Child Development (journal)|Child Development]] | volume = 67 | issue = 4 | pages = 1555&ndash;1571 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-8624.1996.tb01814.x | pmid = 8890500 | date = August 1996 | ref = harv }}</ref> Another indicator of gender essentialism in child development is how they begin to employ essentialist manifestation as a tool for reasoning and perceiving gender stereotyping from as young as 24 months.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Poulin-Dubois | first1 = Diane | last2 = Serbin | first2 = Lisa A. | last3 = Eichstedt | first3 = Julie A. | last4 = Sen | first4 = Maya G. | last5 = Beissel | first5 = Clara F. | title = Men don't put on make-up: toddlers' knowledge of the gender stereotyping of household activities | journal = Social Development | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 166&ndash;181 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/1467-9507.00193 | date = May 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n=== Post-structuralism ===\n\n{{Main|Post-structuralism}}\n{{One source|section|date=October 2017}}\n\n[[Poststructuralism]] indicates \"a field of critical practices that cannot be totalized and that, therefore, interrogate the formative and exclusionary power of sexual difference\", says Butler.<ref name=\":33\">{{cite book | last = Butler | first = Judith|last2 = Wallach Scott|first2 = Joan | author-link1 = Judith Butler | author-link2 = Joan Wallach Scott | title = Feminists theorize the political | publisher = Routledge | location = New York Oxfordshire, England | year = 1992 | isbn = 9780203723999 }}</ref> Therefore, through the poststructuralist lens, the critique of gender essentialism is possible because poststructuralist theory generates analyses, critiques, and political interventions, and opens up a political imaginary for feminism that is otherwise constrained.<ref name=\":33\" /> Feminist poststructuralism does not designate a position from which one operates, but offers a set of tools and terms to be \"reused and rethought, exposed as strategic instruments and effects, and subjected to a critical reinscription and redeployment\".<ref name=\":33\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Empathizing\u2013systemizing theory]]\n* [[Essentialism]]\n* [[French post-structuralist feminism]]\n* [[Gendered sexuality]]\n* [[Neuroscience of sex differences]]\n* [[Neuroplasticity]]\n* [[The NeuroGenderings Network]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Rippon | first1 = Gina | last2 = Jordan-Young | first2 = Rebecca | last3 = Fine | first3 = Cordelia | last4 = Kaiser | first4 = Anelis | author-link1 = Gina Rippon | author-link2 = Rebecca Jordan-Young | author-link3 = Cordelia Fine | author-link4 = Anelis Kaiser | title = Recommendations for sex/gender neuroimaging research: key principles and implications for research design, analysis and interpretation | journal = Frontiers in Human Neuroscience | volume = 8 | issue = | pages = 650 | publisher = [[Frontiers Media|Frontiers]] | doi = 10.3389/fnhum.2014.00650 | pmid = 25221493 | pmc = 4147717 | date = 28 August 2014 | ref = harv }}\n\n[[Category:Feminist terminology]]\n[[Category:Feminist theory]]\n[[Category:Social constructionism]]\n[[Category:Essentialism]]\n", "name_user": "86.178.15.61", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gender_essentialism"}
{"title_page": "Astrological sign", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Constellation]]s}}\n{{for|differences between systems|Sidereal and tropical astrology|Zodiac#Table of dates{{!}}Zodiac}}\n{{redirect|Birth sign|the album by George Freeman|Birth Sign (album)}}\n{{short description|Twelve 30\u00b0 sectors of the ecliptic, as defined by Western astrology}}\n[[File:Zodiac in The Sky, pp. 40\u201341.jpg|thumb|360px|The twelve signs of the zodiac, miniatures from a [[book of hours]]. (''The Sky: Order and Chaos'' by [[Jean-Pierre Verdet]], from the '[[New Horizons (Thames & Hudson)|New Horizons]]' series)]]\nIn [[Western astrology]], '''astrological signs''' are the twelve 30\u00b0 sectors of the [[ecliptic]], starting at the [[vernal equinox]] (one of the intersections of the ecliptic with the [[celestial equator]]), also known as the First Point of Aries. The order of the astrological signs is [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]], [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]], [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]], [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]], [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]], [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]], [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]], [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]], [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]], [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]], [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]] and [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]. Each sector was named for a constellation it was passing through in times of naming.\n\nThe concept of the [[zodiac]] originated in [[Babylonian astrology]], and was later influenced by [[Hellenistic astrology|Hellenistic]] culture. According to [[astrology]], celestial phenomena relate to human activity on the principle of \"[[Macrocosm and microcosm|as above, so below]]\", so that the signs are held to represent characteristic modes of expression.<ref>Mayo (1979), p. 35.</ref> Modern discoveries about the true nature of celestial objects have undermined the theoretical basis for assigning meaning to astrological signs, and empirical scientific investigation has shown that predictions and recommendations based on these systems are not accurate.<ref name=\"Cosmic\">{{cite book |author1=Jeffrey Bennett |author2=Megan Donohue |author3=Nicholas Schneider |author4=Mark Voit |title=The cosmic perspective |url=https://archive.org/details/astronomymediawo04lopr |url-access=registration |year=2007 |publisher=Pearson/Addison-Wesley |location=San Francisco, CA |isbn=0-8053-9283-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/astronomymediawo04lopr/page/82 82\u201384] |edition=4th}}</ref>{{rp|85;}}<ref name=Zarka>{{cite journal |last=Zarka |first=Philippe |title=Astronomy and astrology |journal=Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union |year=2011 |volume=5 |issue=S260 |pages=420\u2013425 |doi=10.1017/S1743921311002602|url=https://zenodo.org/record/890932/files/article.pdf }}</ref>{{rp|424}} Astrology is generally regarded as [[pseudoscience]].\n\nVarious approaches to measuring and dividing the sky are currently used by differing systems of astrology, although the tradition of the Zodiac's names and symbols remain consistent. Western astrology measures from [[Equinox]] and [[Solstice]] points (points relating to equal, longest and shortest days of the [[tropical year]]), while [[Jyoti\u1e63a]] or [[Vedic astrology]] measures along the equatorial plane ([[sidereal year]]). [[Precession]] results in Western astrology's zodiacal divisions not corresponding in the current era to the [[constellations]] that carry similar names,<ref>Bobrick (2005), pp. 10, 23.</ref> while [[Jyoti\u1e63a]] measurements still correspond with the background constellations.<ref>Johnsen (2004).</ref>\n\n== Western zodiac signs ==\n=== Zodiac history and symbolism ===\n{{main|Zodiac}}\n{{further|Babylonian astrology|Hellenistic astrology|Ancient Egyptian astronomy}}\n[[Image:Sign cusps.png|250px|thumb|right|The twelve ecliptic signs. Each dot marks the start of a sign and they are separated by 30\u00b0. The intersection of the celestial equator and the ecliptic define the equinoctial points: First Point of Aries ([[Image:Aries.svg|11px]]) and First Point of Libra ([[Image:Libra.svg|11px]]). The [[great circle]] containing the celestial poles and the ecliptic poles (P and P'), intersect the ecliptic at 0\u00b0 Cancer ([[Image:Cancer.svg|11px]]) and 0\u00b0 Capricorn ([[Image:Capricorn.svg|12px]]). In this illustration, the Sun is schematically positioned at the start of Aquarius ([[Image:Aquarius.svg|11px]]).]]\n\nWhile Western astrology is essentially a product of Greco-Roman culture,{{Citation needed|reason=unclear as to why this is the case|date=June 2019}} some of its more basic concepts originated in Babylon. Isolated references to celestial \"signs\" in Sumerian sources are insufficient to speak of a Sumerian zodiac.<ref>Rochberg (1998), p. ''ix''.</ref> Specifically, the division of the ecliptic in twelve equal sectors is a Babylonian conceptual construction.<ref>Sachs (1948), p. 289.</ref>\n\nBy the 4th century BC, [[Babylonia]]n astronomy and its system of celestial omens had an influence on the culture of [[ancient Greece]], as did the astrology of [[ancient Egypt]] by late 2nd century BC. This resulted, unlike the Mesopotamian tradition, in a strong focus on the birth chart of the individual and in the creation of [[Horoscopic astrology]], employing the use of the [[Ascendant]] (the rising degree of the ecliptic, at the time of birth), and of the twelve [[House (astrology)|houses]]. Association of the astrological signs with [[Empedocles]]' four classical [[Classical element|elements]] was another important development in the characterization of the twelve signs.\n\nThe body of astrological knowledge by the 2nd century AD is described in Ptolemy's ''[[Tetrabiblos]]'', a work that was responsible for astrology's successful spread across Europe and the Middle East, and remained a reference for almost seventeen centuries as later traditions made few substantial changes to its core teachings.\n\nThe following table enumerates the twelve divisions of celestial longitude, with the Latin names (still widely used) and the English translation (gloss), which express the [[constellation]] they are named for. The longitude [[Interval (mathematics)#Notations for intervals|intervals]], are treated as closed for the first endpoint (''a'') and open for the second (''b'') \u2013 for instance, 30\u00b0 of longitude is the first point of Taurus, not part of Aries. The sign numbers, 0 through 11, are seen instead of the symbols in some astronomical works.\n\nAny association of calendar dates with these signs only makes sense when referring to [[Sun sign astrology]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Sign\n! scope=\"col\" | Symbol\n! scope=\"col\" | Number\n! scope=\"col\" | Ecliptic longitude<br>(''a'' \u2264 {{math|''&lambda;''}} < ''b'')\n! scope=\"col\" | Gloss\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]]\n|[[Image:Aries.svg|20px]]\n|0\n|0\u00b0 to 30\u00b0\n|The [[Sheep|Ram]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]]\n|[[Image:Taurus.svg|20px]]\n|1\n|30\u00b0 to 60\u00b0\n|The [[Bull]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]]\n|[[Image:Gemini.svg|20px]]\n|2\n|60\u00b0 to 90\u00b0\n|The [[Twin]]s\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]]\n|[[Image:Cancer.svg|20px]]\n|3\n|90\u00b0 to 120\u00b0\n|The [[Crab]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]]\n|[[Image:Leo.svg|20px]]\n|4\n|120\u00b0 to 150\u00b0\n|The [[Lion]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]]\n|[[Image:Virgo.svg|20px]]\n|5\n|150\u00b0 to 180\u00b0\n|The [[Maiden]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]]\n|[[Image:Libra.svg|24px]]\n|6\n|180\u00b0 to 210\u00b0\n|The [[Weighing scale|Scales]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]]\n|[[Image:Scorpio.svg|20px]]\n|7\n|210\u00b0 to 240\u00b0\n|The [[Scorpion]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]]\n|[[Image:Sagittarius.svg|20px]]\n|8\n|240\u00b0 to 270\u00b0\n|The [[Archery|Archer]] ([[Centaur]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]]\n|[[Image:Capricorn.svg|26px]]\n|9\n|270\u00b0 to 300\u00b0\n|The [[Goat]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]]\n|[[Image:Aquarius.svg|24px]]\n|10\n|300\u00b0 to 330\u00b0\n|The [[water carrier|Water-bearer]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]\n|[[Image:Pisces.svg|20px]]\n|11\n|330\u00b0 to 360\u00b0\n|The [[Fishes]]\n|}\n\n=== Polarity and the four elements ===\n{{main|Triplicity}}\n{{Further|Classical element}}\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n\n[[Image:Sign position example.svg|220px|thumb|right|A simple diagram displaying the planets' sign positions on May 16th, 2012. The signs are colored according to the associated element. Each planet is represented by a [[Astrological symbols|glyph]] next to its longitude within the sign. Additional symbols may be added to represent [[apparent retrograde motion]] ([[File:Retrograde-symbol.svg|11px]]), or apparent stationary moment (shift from retrograde to direct, or vice versa: S).]]\n\n[[Empedocles]], a fifth-century BC Greek philosopher, identified Fire, Earth, Air, and Water as [[classical element|elements]]. He explained the nature of the universe as an interaction of two opposing principles called love and strife manipulating the four elements, and stated that these four elements were all equal, of the same age, that each rules its own province, and each possesses its own individual character. Different mixtures of these elements produced the different natures of things. Empedocles said that those who were born with near equal proportions of the four elements are more intelligent and have the most exact perceptions.<ref name=\"Charlie Higgins\">{{cite web|url=http://accessnewage.com/Articles/astro/HIGELEMS.HTM |title=Astrology and The Four Elements |author=Charlie Higgins |year=1997 |accessdate=2009-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103102752/http://accessnewage.com/articles/astro/HIGELEMS.HTM |archivedate=2010-01-03 |df= }}</ref>\n\nEach sign is associated with one of the [[classical element]]s (fire, air, earth, and water),<ref name=\"RobLeo\">Pelletier, Robert, and Leonard Cataldo (1984). ''Be Your Own Astrologer''. London: Pan Books. pp. 43\u201344</ref><ref name=Pottenger>Pottenger, Maritha (1991). ''Astro Essentials''. San Diego: ACS Publications. pp. 31\u201336.</ref> and these can also be grouped according to polarity (positive or negative): Fire and Air signs are considered [[Positive sign (astrology)|positive signs]] while Water and Earth signs are considered [[Negative sign (astrology)|negative signs]]. The four astrological elements are also considered as a direct equivalent to [[Four temperaments|Hippocrates' personality types]] (sanguine = air; choleric = fire; melancholic = earth; phlegmatic = water). A modern approach looks at elements as \"the energy substance of experience\"<ref name=\"Arroyo27\">Arroyo (1989), p. 27.</ref> and the next table tries to summarize their description through keywords.<ref>Arroyo (1989), pp. 30\u201334</ref><ref>Hone (1978), p. 42</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Polarity\n!Element\n!Symbol<ref>Glyphs from the [[alchemical symbol]]ogy.</ref>\n!Keywords\n!Signs\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Positive (Male)<br>(self-expressive)\n| [[Fire (classical element)|Fire]]\n| [[File:Alchemy fire symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Enthusiasm, drive to express self, faith\n|Aries, Leo, Sagittarius\n|-\n| [[Air (classical element)|Air]]\n| [[File:Alchemy air symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Communication, socialization, conceptualization\n|Gemini, Libra, Aquarius\n|- align=center \n|rowspan=\"2\"| Negative (Female)<br>(self-containing)\n| [[Earth (classical element)|Earth]]\n| [[File:Alchemy earth symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Practicality, caution, material world\n|Taurus, Virgo, Capricorn\n|-\n| [[Water (classical element)|Water]]\n| [[File:Alchemy water symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Emotion, empathy, sensitivity\n|Cancer, Scorpio, Pisces\n|- align=center\n|}\nClassification according to element has gained such importance, that some astrologers start their interpretation of a [[natal chart]], by studying the balance of elements shown by the position of [[Planets in astrology|planets]] and [[Angle (astrology)|angles]]<ref>Arroyo (1975). pp.&nbsp;131\u2013140.</ref> (especially the Sun, the Moon and the Ascendant signs).\n\n=== The three modalities ===\n<!-- \n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nEach of the four elements manifests in three modalities: Cardinal, Fixed and Mutable.<ref>Arroyo (1989), p. 29.</ref> As each modality comprehends four signs, these are also known as Quadruplicities.<ref name=\"RobLeo\"/><ref name=Pottenger/> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Modality !! Symbol<ref>As used in Sepharial's \"The Manual of Astrology\"-Brazilian edition (1988) by Editora Nova Fronteira S/A, Rio de Janeiro</ref>!! Keywords<ref>Hone (1978), p. 40</ref><ref>Arroyo (1989), p. 30</ref>!! Signs\n|-\n| [[Cardinal sign (astrology)|Cardinal]] || [[File:Cardinal symbol.svg|20px]] || Action, dynamic, initiative, great force || Aries, Cancer, Libra, Capricorn\n|-\n| [[Fixed sign|Fixed]] || [[File:Fixed symbol.svg|20px]] || Resistance to change, great willpower, inflexible || Taurus, Leo, Scorpio, Aquarius\n|-\n| [[Mutable sign|Mutable]] || [[File:Mutable symbol.svg|20px]] || Adaptability, flexibility, resourcefulness || Gemini, Virgo, Sagittarius, Pisces\n|- align=center\n|}\n\nThe combination of element and modality provides a basic sign characterization. For instance, Capricorn is a cardinal earth sign, meaning that it is associated with action (cardinal modality) in the material world (earth element).<ref>Hone (1978), p. 75</ref> The next table displays the twelve combinations of elements and modalities.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Element\n! scope=\"col\" | Fire\n! scope=\"col\" | Earth\n! scope=\"col\" | Air\n! scope=\"col\" | Water\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Cardinal\n|Aries\n|Capricorn\n|Libra\n|Cancer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fixed\n|Leo\n|Taurus\n|Aquarius\n|Scorpio\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mutable\n|Sagittarius\n|Virgo\n|Gemini\n|Pisces\n|}\n\n=== Planetary rulerships ===\n{{See also|Domicile (astrology)}}\n[[File:Acta Eruditorum - II astrologia, 1716 \u2013 BEIC 13388141.jpg|thumb|Representation of the western astrological signs in a 1716 ''[[Acta Eruditorum]]'' table illustration]]\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n\nRulership is the connection between [[Planets in astrology|planet]] and correlated sign and [[House (astrology)|house]].<ref>Hone (1978), p. 22</ref> In traditional [[history of astrology|Western astrology]], each sign is ruled by one of the seven visible planets (note that in [[astrology]], the Sun and Moon are termed \"The Lights\" or fixed stars, while the other bodies are called planets or ''wanderers'', i.e. wandering stars as opposed to the fixed stars). The traditional rulerships are as follows: [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]] ([[Mars]]), [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]] ([[Venus]]), [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]] ([[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]), [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]] ([[Moon]]), [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]] ([[Sun]]), [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]] ([[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]), [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]] ([[Venus]]), [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]] ([[Pluto]]), [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]] ([[Jupiter]]), [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]] ([[Saturn]]), [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]] ([[Uranus]]), and [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]] ([[Neptune]]).<ref name=\"astrologynow.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astrologynow.com/carolwillis/Rulerships.txt |title=Rulerships |author=Carol Wills |year=2007 |website=astrologynow.com |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070127194954/http://www.astrologynow.com/carolwillis/Rulerships.txt |archivedate=2007-01-27 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shamos |first1=Geoffery |title=Astrology as a Social Framework: The 'Children of Planets', 1400\u20131600 |journal=[[Journal for the Study of Religion, Nature and Culture]] |date=2013 |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=434\u2013460 |doi=10.1558/jsrnc.v7i4.434}}</ref>\n\n[[Psychological astrology|Psychologically-oriented]] astrologers often believe that [[Saturn]] is the ruler or co-ruler of Aquarius instead of Uranus; [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] is the ruler or co-ruler of Pisces instead of Jupiter, and that [[Pluto (mythology)|Pluto]] is the ruler or co-ruler of Scorpio instead of Mars. Some astrologers<ref name=\"Planet Waves\">{{cite web|title=Chiron as True Ruler of Virgo?|accessdate= July 18, 2014|url= http://www.planetwaves.net/cainer/archive/003530.php}}</ref> believe that the planetoid [[Chiron]] may be the ruler of Virgo, while other group of modern astrologers claim that [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] is the ruler of Taurus instead.\n\n===Dates table===\nThe following table shows both traditional<ref name=\"astrologynow.com\"/> and modern<ref>Hone (1978), p. 21.</ref> rulerships.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Symbol\n!Unicode <br>{{abbr|Char|Character}}\n!Sign names\n!Dates \n!Ruling <br>celestial body<br>\nModern\n!Ruling <br>celestial body<br>\nClassical\n|-\n|[[Image:Aries.svg|20px]]\n|\u2648\n|[[Aries (astrology)|Aries]]\n|March 21 \u2013 April 19\n|Mars\n|Mars\n|-\n|[[Image:Taurus.svg|20px]]\n|\u2649\n|[[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]]\n|April 20 \u2013 May 20\n|Venus\n|Venus\n|-\n|[[Image:Gemini.svg|20px]]\n|\u264a\n|[[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]]\n|May 21 \u2013 June 20\n|Mercury\n|Mercury\n|-\n|[[Image:Cancer.svg|20px]]\n|\u264b\n|[[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]]\n|June 21 \u2013 July 22\n|Moon\n|Moon\n|-\n|[[Image:Leo.svg|20px]]\n|\u264c\n|[[Leo (astrology)|Leo]]\n|July 23 \u2013 August 22\n|Sun\n|Sun\n|-\n|[[Image:Virgo.svg|20px]]\n|\u264d\n|[[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]]\n|August 23 \u2013 September 22\n|Mercury\n|Earth\n|-\n|[[Image:Libra.svg|25px]]\n|\u264e\n|[[Libra (astrology)|Libra]]\n|September 23 \u2013 October 22\n|Venus\n|Venus\n|-\n|[[Image:Scorpio.svg|20px]]\n|\u264f\n|[[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]]\n|October 23 \u2013 November 21\n|Pluto\n|Mars\n|-\n|[[Image:Sagittarius.svg|20px]]\n|\u2650\n|[[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]]\n|November 22 \u2013 December 21\n|Jupiter\n|Jupiter\n|-\n|[[Image:Capricorn.svg|25px]]\n|\u2651\n|[[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]]\n|December 22 \u2013 January 19\n|Saturn\n|Saturn\n|-\n|[[Image:Aquarius.svg|25px]]\n|\u2652\n|[[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]]\n|January 20 \u2013 February 18\n|Uranus\n|Saturn\n|-\n|[[Image:Pisces.svg|20px]]\n|\u2653\n|[[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]\n|February 19 \u2013 March 20\n|Neptune\n|Jupiter\n|-\n|}\n\nThe twelves signs each have opposites, resulting in six opposite couples. Fire and Air elements are opposites and Earth and Water elements are opposites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/opposizione|title=Opposition|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref> Spring signs are opposite to autumn ones, and winter signs are opposite to summer ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2994-aria|title=The element of Air|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2992-fuoco|title=The element of Fire|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2993-acqua|title=The element of Water|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2995-terra|title=The element of Earth|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref>\n* Aries is opposite to Libra\n* Cancer is opposite to Capricorn\n* Gemini is opposite to Sagittarius\n* Pisces is opposite to Virgo\n* Taurus is opposite to Scorpio\n* Leo is opposite to Aquarius\n\n=== Dignity and detriment, exaltation and fall ===\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nA traditional belief of astrology, known as [[essential dignity]], is the idea that the Sun, Moon and planets are more powerful and effective in some signs than others, because the basic nature of both is held to be in harmony. By contrast, they are held to find some signs to be weak or difficult to operate in because their natures are thought to be in conflict. The most important of these categories are Dignity, Detriment, Exaltation and Fall.\n\n* '''[[Essential dignity|Dignity]]''' and '''[[Detriment (astrology)|Detriment]]''': A [[Planets in astrology|planet]] is strengthened or '''dignified''' if it falls within the sign that it rules. In other words, it is said to exercise ''[[Domicile (astrology)|Rulership]]'' of the sign. For example, the Moon in Cancer is considered \"strong\" (well-dignified). Seventeenth century astrologer [[William Lilly]] compared rulership to a king on his throne, with considerable dignity. If a planet is in the sign opposite that which it rules (or is dignified), it is said to be weakened or in '''Detriment''' (for example, the Moon in Capricorn).<ref name=\"glossary\">\"Glossary of Astrological Terms\". Logos, Asaa 1998\u20132004. 26 Nov 2007. {{cite web|url=http://logosastrology.dk/glossary.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122142135/http://logosastrology.dk/glossary.htm |archivedate=2008-01-22 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn traditional astrology, other levels of Dignity are recognised in addition to Rulership. These are known as Exaltation (see below), [[Triplicity]], [[Terms or bounds]], and Face or [[Decans|Decan]], which together are known as describing a planet's ''[[Essential dignity]]'', the quality or ability to give of one's true nature. Contemporary traditional astrologers like [[John Frawley (astrologer)|John Frawley]] or [[J Lee Lehman]] explain further on the concept of Essential Dignity.<ref name=\"glossary\" />\n\n* '''[[Exaltation (astrology)|Exaltation]]''' and '''[[Astrological fall|Fall]]''': In addition, a planet is also strengthened when it is in its sign of '''Exaltation'''. In traditional horary astrology, Exaltation denotes a level of dignity somewhat exaggerated compared to rulership. Exaltation was considered to give the planet (or what it signified in a horary chart) dignity, with the metaphor of an honoured guest \u2013 who is the centre of attention but the extent of their ability to act is limited. Examples of planets in their Exaltation are: Saturn (Libra), Sun (Aries), Venus (Pisces), Moon (Taurus), Mercury (Virgo, although some disagree to this classification), Mars (Capricorn), Jupiter (Cancer). A planet in the opposite sign of its Exaltation is said to be in its '''Fall''', and thus weakened, perhaps seemingly more so than Detriment. The Planet in fall is passively rejected or ignored by the sign that it's in. It can be likened to a mayor of a rival city trying to make suggestions to the hosting mayor for how he should run his city: The host mayor finds it difficult to trust him and cannot see how his input could have relevancy to his city. The people of the city feel the same as their ruler. The result is impasse and failure on behalf of both mayors and the city.<ref name=\"glossary\" /> There is no agreement as to the signs in which the three extra-Saturnian planets may be considered to be exalted.<ref>Hone (1978), p. 144</ref>\n\nThe following table summarizes the positions described above:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Planet (Symbol) !! Dignity !! Detriment !! Exaltation !! Fall\n|-\n| '''Sun''' ([[File:Sun symbol.svg|15px|Sol]]) || Leo || Cancer || Aries || Libra\n|-\n| '''Moon''' ([[File:Moon symbol crescent.svg|15px|First quarter moon]]) || Cancer || Leo || Taurus || Scorpio\n|-\n| '''Mercury''' ([[File:Mercury symbol.svg|15px|Mercury]]) || Gemini || Sagittarius and Pisces || Aquarius || Leo\n|-\n| '''Venus''' ([[File:Venus symbol.svg|15px|Venus]]) || Libra and Taurus || Aries and Scorpio || Pisces || Virgo\n|-\n| '''Mars''' ([[File:Mars symbol.svg|15px|Mars]]) || Aries and Scorpio || Libra and Taurus || Capricorn || Cancer\n|-\n| '''Jupiter''' ([[File:Jupiter symbol.svg|15px|Jupiter]]) || Sagittarius and Pisces || Gemini and Virgo || Cancer || Capricorn\n|-\n| '''Saturn''' ([[File:Saturn symbol.svg|15px|Saturn]]) || Capricorn and Aquarius || Cancer and Leo || Libra || Aries\n|-\n!Earth \n|Virgo\n|Scorpio\n|Leo\n|Cancer\n|}\n\nIn addition to essential dignity, the traditional astrologer considers ''[[Accidental dignity]]'' of planets. This is placement by [[astrological house|house]] in the chart under examination. Accidental dignity is the planet's \"ability to act.\" So we might have, for example, Moon in Cancer, dignified by rulership, is placed in the 12th house it would have little scope to express its good nature.<ref>{{cite web|title=Accidental Dignity|publisher= Astrological Dictionary 1998\u20132007|website= www.gotohoroscope.com|date= 26 November 2007|url= http://www.gotohoroscope.com/dictionary/astrological/5.html}}</ref> The 12th is a cadent house as are the 3rd, 6th and 9th and planets in these houses are considered weak or afflicted. On the other hand, Moon in the 1st, 4th, 7th or 10th would be more able to act as these are Angular houses. Planets in Succedent houses of the chart (2nd, 5th, 8th, 11th) are generally considered to be of medium ability to act. Besides Accidental Dignity, there are a range of ''Accidental Debilities'', such as retrogradation, Under the Sun's Beams, Combust, and so forth.\n\n=== Additional classifications ===\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n{{Details|Decans}}\nEach sign can be divided into three 10\u00b0 sectors known as decans or decanates, though these have fallen into disuse. The first decanate is said to be most emphatically of its own nature and is ruled by the sign ruler.<ref>Hone (1978), p.&nbsp;87</ref> The next decanate is sub-ruled by the planet ruling the next sign in the same triplicity. The last decanate is sub-ruled by the next in order in the same triplicity.<ref>Hone (1978), p.&nbsp;88</ref>\n\nWhile the element and modality of a sign are together sufficient to define it, they can be grouped to indicate their symbolism. The first four signs, Aries, Taurus, Gemini and Cancer, form the group of personal signs. The next four signs, Leo, Virgo, Libra and Scorpio form the group of interpersonal signs. The last four signs of the zodiac, Sagittarius, Capricorn, Aquarius and Pisces, form the group of transpersonal signs.<ref name=\"spiritsingles.com\">\"An Introduction to Astrology.\" Spiritsingles.com 25 Nov.2007. {{cite web|url=http://www.spiritsingles.com/Astrology/aboutAstrology.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209083130/http://www.spiritsingles.com/Astrology/aboutAstrology.cfm |archivedate=2007-12-09 |df= }}</ref>\n\nDane Rudhyar presented the tropical zodiac primary factors,<ref>Rudhyar (1943)</ref> used in the curriculum of the RASA School of Astrology. The tropical zodiac is the zodiac of seasonal factors as opposed to the sidereal zodiac (constellation factors). The primary seasonal factors are based on the changing ratio of sunlight and darkness across the year. The first factor is whether the chosen time falls in the half of the year when daylight is increasing, or the half of the year when darkness is increasing. The second factor is whether the chosen time falls in the half of the year when there is more daylight than darkness, or the half when there is more darkness than daylight. The third factor is which of the four seasons the chosen time falls in, defined by the first two factors. Thus<ref name=ArmstrongFactors>{{cite web|title=The Signs and the Houses|first= Robin |last=Armstrong|publisher= RASA School of Astrology|year= 2009 |url=http://www.rasa.ws/index.php/rasa-library-articles-signs-and-houses-}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I Ching: The Sequence of Change|first= Robin|last= Armstrong|publisher= RA Publications |year=2009 |url=http://thewakingdream.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1392&Itemid=1551}}</ref> \n* The ''winter'' season is when daylight is increasing and there is more darkness than daylight.\n* The ''spring'' season is when daylight is increasing and there is more daylight than darkness.\n* The ''summer'' season is when darkness is increasing and there is more daylight than darkness.\n* The ''autumn'' season is when darkness is increasing and there is more darkness than daylight.\n\n== Indian astrology ==\n{{further|Hindu astrology}}\nIn Indian astrology, there are five elements: fire, earth, air, water, and ether. The master of fire is Mars, while Mercury is of earth, Saturn of air, Venus of water, and Jupiter of ether.\n\n[[Jyotish]] astrology recognises twelve zodiac signs (R\u0101\u015bi),<ref>Sutton (1999) pp. 74\u201392.</ref> that correspond to those in Western astrology. The relation of the signs to the elements is the same in the two systems.\n\n=== Nakshatras ===\n{{main|Nakshatra}}\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nA '''nakshatra''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0928\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930, [[Sanskrit]] ''{{IAST|nakshatra}}'', from ''{{IAST|naksha-}}'' 'map', and ''{{IAST|tra-}}'' 'guard'), or '''lunar mansion''', is one of the 27 divisions of the sky identified by the prominent star(s), as used in [[Hindu astronomy]] and [[Jyotisha|astrology]] ([[Jyotisha]]).<ref>Sutton (1999), p.&nbsp;168.</ref> \"Nakshatra\" in Sanskrit and Tamil means a \"star.\"\n\n== Chinese zodiac signs ==\n{{main|Chinese zodiac}}\n\nChinese astrological signs operate on cycles of years, lunar months, and two-hour periods of the day (also known as ''shichen''). A particular feature of the Chinese zodiac is its operation in a [[Sexagenary cycle|60-year cycle]] in combination with the [[Wu Xing|Five Phases]] of [[Chinese astrology]] ([[Wood (Wu Xing)|Wood]], [[Fire (Wu Xing)|Fire]], [[Metal (Wu Xing)|Metal]], [[Water (Wu Xing)|Water]] and [[Earth (Wu Xing)|Earth]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://big5.china.com.cn/culture/txt/2009-02/16/content_17286701.htm |title='Almanac' 'lunar' zodiac beginning of spring as the boundary dislocation? \u2013 China Network |date=16 February 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2011}}</ref>\nNevertheless, some researches say that there is an obvious relationship between the Chinese 12-year cycle and zodiac constellations: each year of the cycle corresponds to a certain disposal of Jupiter. For example, in the year of [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] Jupiter is in the Sign of Gemini, in the year of [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] Jupiter is in the Sign of Cancer and so on. So the Chinese 12-year calendar is a solar-lunar-jovian calendar.\n\n=== Zodiac symbolism ===\nThe following table shows the twelve signs and their attributes.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Sign\n!Yin/Yang\n!Direction\n!Season\n!Fixed Element\n!Trine\n|-\n|[[Mouse (zodiac)|Mouse]]\n|Yang\n|North\n|Mid-Winter\n|Water\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]]\n|Yin\n|North\n|Late Winter\n|Earth\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]]\n|Yang\n|East\n|Early Spring\n|Wood\n|3rd\n|-\n|[[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]]\n|Yin\n|East\n|Mid-Spring\n|Wood\n|4th\n|-\n|[[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]]\n|Yang\n|East\n|Late Spring\n|Earth\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]]\n|Yin\n|South\n|Early Summer\n|Fire\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]]\n|Yang\n|South\n|Mid-Summer\n|Fire\n|3rd\n|-\n|[[Sheep (zodiac)|Sheep]]\n|Yin\n|South\n|Late Summer\n|Earth\n|4th\n|-\n|[[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]]\n|Yang\n|West\n|Early Autumn\n|Metal\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]]\n|Yin\n|West\n|Mid-Autumn\n|Metal\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]]\n|Yang\n|West\n|Late Autumn\n|Earth\n|3rd\n|-\n|[[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]]\n|Yin\n|North\n|Early Winter\n|Water\n|4th\n|}\n\n=== The twelve signs ===\n\n[[Image:China 24 cardinal directions.png|thumb|250px|Chart showing the 24 cardinal directions and the symbols of the sign associated with them.]]\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nIn [[Chinese astrology]], the zodiac of twelve animal sign represents twelve different types of personality. The zodiac traditionally begins with the sign of the [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]], and there are many stories about the [[Origins of the Chinese Zodiac]] which explain why this is so. When the twelve zodiac signs are part of the 60-year calendar in combination with the four elements, they are traditionally called the twelve [[Earthly Branches]]. The Chinese zodiac follows the [[Lunisolar calendar|lunisolar]] [[Chinese calendar]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Novak|first1=Sarah|title=The Chinese Zodiac|journal=Faces|volume=34|pages=42}}</ref> and thus the \"changeover\" days in a month (when one sign changes to another sign) vary each year. The following are the twelve zodiac signs in order.<ref name=Lau>Theodora Lau, ''Ibid'', pp. 2\u20138, 30\u20135, 60\u20134, 88\u201394, 118\u201324, 148\u201353, 178\u201384, 208\u201313, 238\u201344, 270\u201378, 306\u201312, 338\u201344, 2005</ref>\n\n# {{lang|zh|\u5b50}} [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] (Yang, 1st Trine, Fixed Element Water): [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] years include 1900, 1912, 1924, 1936, 1948, 1960, 1972, 1984, 1996, 2008, 2020, 2032. The [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] are 11pm \u2013 1am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u4e11}} [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] (Yin, 2nd Trine, Fixed Element Earth:<ref name=\"Wu\" /> [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] years include 1901, 1913, 1925, 1937, 1949, 1961, 1973, 1985, 1997, 2009, 2021, 2033. The [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] are 1am \u2013 3am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u5bc5}} [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] (Yang, 3rd Trine, Fixed Element Wood): [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] years include 1902, 1914, 1926, 1938, 1950, 1962, 1974, 1986, 1998, 2010, 2022, 2034. The [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] are 3am \u2013 5am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u536f}} [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] (Yin, 4th Trine, Fixed Element Wood): [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] Years include 1903, 1915, 1927, 1939, 1951, 1963, 1975, 1987, 1999, 2011, 2023, 2035. The [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] are 5am \u2013 7am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u8fb0}} [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] (Yang, 1st Trine, Fixed Element Earth<ref name=\"Wu\" />): [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] years include 1904, 1916, 1928, 1940, 1952, 1964, 1976, 1988, 2000, 2012, 2024, 2036. The [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] are 7am \u2013 9am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u5df3}} [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] (Yin, 2nd Trine, Fixed Element Fire): [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] years include 1905, 1917, 1929, 1941, 1953, 1965, 1977, 1989, 2001, 2013, 2025, 2037. The [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] are 9am \u2013 11am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u5348}} [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] (Yang, 3rd Trine, Fixed Element Fire): [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] years include 1906, 1918, 1930, 1942, 1954, 1966, 1978, 1990, 2002, 2014, 2026, 2038. The [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] are 11am \u2013 1pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u672a}} [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] (Yin, 4th Trine, Fixed Element Earth<ref name=\"Wu\" />): [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] years include 1907, 1919, 1931, 1943, 1955, 1967, 1979, 1991, 2003, 2015, 2027, 2039. The [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] are 1pm \u2013 3pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u7533}} [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] (Yang, 1st Trine, Fixed Element Metal): [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] years include 1908, 1920, 1932, 1944, 1956, 1968, 1980, 1992, 2004, 2016, 2028, 2040. The [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] are 3pm \u2013 5pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u9149}} [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] (Yin, 2nd Trine, Fixed Element Metal): [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] years include 1909, 1921, 1933, 1945, 1957, 1969, 1981, 1993, 2005, 2017, 2029, 2041. The [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] are 5pm \u2013 7pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u620c}} [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] (Yang, 3rd Trine, Fixed Element Earth<ref name=\"Wu\" />): [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] years include 1910, 1922, 1934, 1946, 1958, 1970, 1982, 1994, 2006, 2018, 2030, 2042. The [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] are 7pm \u2013 9pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u4ea5}} [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] (Yin, 4th Trine, Fixed Element Water): [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] years include 1911, 1923, 1935, 1947, 1959, 1971, 1983, 1995, 2007, 2019, 2031, 2043. The [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] are 9pm \u2013 11pm.\n\n=== The five elements ===\n\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n\n* '''[[Tree (Wu Xing)|Wood]]''': The wood person has high morals, is self-confident, expansive and co-operative, with wide and varied interests and idealistic goals. The direction associated with Wood is East, and the season is spring, which makes it the fixed element for the animal signs [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] and [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Fire (Wu Xing)|Fire]]''': The fire person has leadership qualities, dynamic passion, and is decisive, self-confident, positive and assertive. The direction associated with Fire is South, and the season is summer, which makes it the fixed element for the animal signs [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] and [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Earth (Wu Xing)|Earth]]''': The earth person is serious, logical and methodical, intelligent, objective and good at planning. The direction associated with Earth is Center.  The season for Earth is the changeover point of the four seasons.  It is the fixed element for the animal signs [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]], [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]], [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] and [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Metal (Wu Xing)|Metal]]''': The metal person is sincere, has fixed values and opinions, is strong of will, and has eloquence of speech.  The direction associated with Metal is West.  The season for Metal is Autumn.  It is the fixed element for the animal signs [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] and [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Water (Wu Xing)|Water]]''': The water person is persuasive, intuitive, and empathetic.  The water person is objective and often sought out for their counsel.  The direction associated with water is North.  The season for Water is Winter.  It is the fixed element for the animal signs [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] and [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]].<ref name=Wu/>\n\nThe five elements operate together with the twelve animal signs in a [[Sexagenary cycle|60-year]] calendar. The five elements appear in the calendar in both their yin and yang forms and are known as the ten [[Celestial stem]]s. When trying to calculate the relevant year of the cycle in relation to the [[Gregorian calendar]], an easy rule to follow is that years that end in an even number are Yang (representing masculine, active and light), those that end with an odd number are Yin (representing feminine, passive and darkness).<ref name=Wu>Chinese Astrology:  Exploring the Eastern Zodiac by Shelly Wu</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n== References ==\n*Arroyo, Stephen (1975). ''Astrology, Psychology and The Four Elements''. California: CCRS Publications\n*Arroyo, Stephen (1989). ''Chart Interpretation Handbook''. California: CCRS Publications. {{ISBN|0-916360-49-0}}\n*Bobrick, Benson (2005). ''The Fated Sky: Astrology in History''. Simon & Schuster. 369 pp.\n*Caiozzo, Anna (2003). ''Images of the Sky.'' Paris-Sorbonne. [https://sites.google.com/site/allzodiacs/ Signs and Constellations.]\n*Eric Francis (2016). \"[http://members.planetwaves.net/why-your-zodiac-sign-is-not-wrong/ Why Your Zodiac Sign is Not Wrong]\"\n*Hone, Margaret (1978). ''The Modern Text-Book of Astrology''. Revised edition. England: L. N. Fowler & Co. Ltd. {{ISBN|085243-357-3}}\n*Johnsen, Linda (2004 March). ''A Thousand Suns: Designing Your Future with Vedic Astrology''. Yes International Publishers.\n*Mayo, Jeff (1979). ''Teach Yourself Astrology''. London: Hodder and Stoughton.\n*Rochberg, Francesca (1998), \"Babylonian Horoscopes\", ''American Philosophical Society'', New Series, Vol. 88, No. 1, pp.&nbsp;i\u2013164. {{doi|10.2307/1006632}}. {{JSTOR|1006632}}.\n*[http://www.khaldea.com/rudhyar/pofl/pofl_p1p1.shtml Rudhyar, Dane (1943). ''Astrological Signs \u2013 The Pulse of Life''.]\n*Sachs, Abraham (1948), \"A Classification of the Babylonian Astronomical Tablets of the Seleucid Period\", ''Journal of Cuneiform Studies'', Vol. 2, No. 4, pp.&nbsp;271\u2013290. {{doi|10.2307/3515929}}. {{JSTOR|3515929}}.\n*Sutton, Komilla (1999). ''The Essentials of Vedic Astrology''. England: The Wessex Astrologer Ltd.\n\n{{astrology-footer}}\n{{Zodiac}}\n{{Chinese Zodiac}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Astrological Sign}}\n[[Category:Astrological signs| ]]\n[[Category:Astrology|Signs]]\n[[Category:Technical factors of astrology]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Constellation]]s}}\n{{for|differences between systems|Sidereal and tropical astrology|Zodiac#Table of dates{{!}}Zodiac}}\n{{redirect|Birth sign|the album by George Freeman|Birth Sign (album)}}\n{{short description|Twelve 30\u00b0 sectors of the ecliptic, as defined by Western astrology}}\n[[File:Zodiac in The Sky, pp. 40\u201341.jpg|thumb|360px|The twelve signs of the zodiac, miniatures from a [[book of hours]]. (''The Sky: Order and Chaos'' by [[Jean-Pierre Verdet]], from the '[[New Horizons (Thames & Hudson)|New Horizons]]' series)]]\nIn [[Western astrology]], '''astrological signs''' are the twelve 30\u00b0 sectors of the [[ecliptic]], starting at the [[vernal equinox]] (one of the intersections of the ecliptic with the [[celestial equator]]), also known as the First Point of Aries. The order of the astrological signs is [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]], [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]], [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]], [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]], [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]], [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]], [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]], [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]], [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]], [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]], [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]] and [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]. Each sector was named for a constellation it was passing through in times of naming.\n\nThe concept of the [[zodiac]] originated in [[Babylonian astrology]], and was later influenced by [[Hellenistic astrology|Hellenistic]] culture. According to [[astrology]], celestial phenomena relate to human activity on the principle of \"[[Macrocosm and microcosm|as above, so below]]\", so that the signs are held to represent characteristic modes of expression.<ref>Mayo (1979), p. 35.</ref> Modern discoveries about the true nature of celestial objects have undermined the theoretical basis for assigning meaning to astrological signs, and empirical scientific investigation has shown that predictions and recommendations based on these systems are not accurate.<ref name=\"Cosmic\">{{cite book |author1=Jeffrey Bennett |author2=Megan Donohue |author3=Nicholas Schneider |author4=Mark Voit |title=The cosmic perspective |url=https://archive.org/details/astronomymediawo04lopr |url-access=registration |year=2007 |publisher=Pearson/Addison-Wesley |location=San Francisco, CA |isbn=0-8053-9283-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/astronomymediawo04lopr/page/82 82\u201384] |edition=4th}}</ref>{{rp|85;}}<ref name=Zarka>{{cite journal |last=Zarka |first=Philippe |title=Astronomy and astrology |journal=Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union |year=2011 |volume=5 |issue=S260 |pages=420\u2013425 |doi=10.1017/S1743921311002602|url=https://zenodo.org/record/890932/files/article.pdf }}</ref>{{rp|424}} Astrology is generally regarded as [[pseudoscience]].\n\nVarious approaches to measuring and dividing the sky are currently used by differing systems of astrology, although the tradition of the Zodiac's names and symbols remain consistent. Western astrology measures from [[Equinox]] and [[Solstice]] points (points relating to equal, longest and shortest days of the [[tropical year]]), while [[Jyoti\u1e63a]] or [[Vedic astrology]] measures along the equatorial plane ([[sidereal year]]). [[Precession]] results in Western astrology's zodiacal divisions not corresponding in the current era to the [[constellations]] that carry similar names,<ref>Bobrick (2005), pp. 10, 23.</ref> while [[Jyoti\u1e63a]] measurements still correspond with the background constellations.<ref>Johnsen (2004).</ref>\n\n== Western zodiac signs ==\n=== Zodiac history and symbolism ===\n{{main|Zodiac}}\n{{further|Babylonian astrology|Hellenistic astrology|Ancient Egyptian astronomy}}\n[[Image:Sign cusps.png|250px|thumb|right|The twelve ecliptic signs. Each dot marks the start of a sign and they are separated by 30\u00b0. The intersection of the celestial equator and the ecliptic define the equinoctial points: First Point of Aries ([[Image:Aries.svg|11px]]) and First Point of Libra ([[Image:Libra.svg|11px]]). The [[great circle]] containing the celestial poles and the ecliptic poles (P and P'), intersect the ecliptic at 0\u00b0 Cancer ([[Image:Cancer.svg|11px]]) and 0\u00b0 Capricorn ([[Image:Capricorn.svg|12px]]). In this illustration, the Sun is schematically positioned at the start of Aquarius ([[Image:Aquarius.svg|11px]]).]]\n\nWhile Western astrology is essentially a product of Greco-Roman culture,{{Citation needed|reason=unclear as to why this is the case|date=June 2019}} some of its more basic concepts originated in Babylon. Isolated references to celestial \"signs\" in Sumerian sources are insufficient to speak of a Sumerian zodiac.<ref>Rochberg (1998), p. ''ix''.</ref> Specifically, the division of the ecliptic in twelve equal sectors is a Babylonian conceptual construction.<ref>Sachs (1948), p. 289.</ref>\n\nBy the 4th century BC, [[Babylonia]]n astronomy and its system of celestial omens had an influence on the culture of [[ancient Greece]], as did the astrology of [[ancient Egypt]] by late 2nd century BC. This resulted, unlike the Mesopotamian tradition, in a strong focus on the birth chart of the individual and in the creation of [[Horoscopic astrology]], employing the use of the [[Ascendant]] (the rising degree of the ecliptic, at the time of birth), and of the twelve [[House (astrology)|houses]]. Association of the astrological signs with [[Empedocles]]' four classical [[Classical element|elements]] was another important development in the characterization of the twelve signs.\n\nThe body of astrological knowledge by the 2nd century AD is described in Ptolemy's ''[[Tetrabiblos]]'', a work that was responsible for astrology's successful spread across Europe and the Middle East, and remained a reference for almost seventeen centuries as later traditions made few substantial changes to its core teachings.\n\nThe following table enumerates the twelve divisions of celestial longitude, with the Latin names (still widely used) and the English translation (gloss), which express the [[constellation]] they are named for. The longitude [[Interval (mathematics)#Notations for intervals|intervals]], are treated as closed for the first endpoint (''a'') and open for the second (''b'') \u2013 for instance, 30\u00b0 of longitude is the first point of Taurus, not part of Aries. The sign numbers, 0 through 11, are seen instead of the symbols in some astronomical works.\n\nAny association of calendar dates with these signs only makes sense when referring to [[Sun sign astrology]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Sign\n! scope=\"col\" | Symbol\n! scope=\"col\" | Number\n! scope=\"col\" | Ecliptic longitude<br>(''a'' \u2264 {{math|''&lambda;''}} < ''b'')\n! scope=\"col\" | Gloss\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]]\n|[[Image:Aries.svg|20px]]\n|0\n|0\u00b0 to 30\u00b0\n|The [[Sheep|Ram]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]]\n|[[Image:Taurus.svg|20px]]\n|1\n|30\u00b0 to 60\u00b0\n|The [[Bull]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]]\n|[[Image:Gemini.svg|20px]]\n|2\n|60\u00b0 to 90\u00b0\n|The [[Twin]]s\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]]\n|[[Image:Cancer.svg|20px]]\n|3\n|90\u00b0 to 120\u00b0\n|The [[Crab]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]]\n|[[Image:Leo.svg|20px]]\n|4\n|120\u00b0 to 150\u00b0\n|The [[Lion]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]]\n|[[Image:Virgo.svg|20px]]\n|5\n|150\u00b0 to 180\u00b0\n|The [[Maiden]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]]\n|[[Image:Libra.svg|24px]]\n|6\n|180\u00b0 to 210\u00b0\n|The [[Weighing scale|Scales]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]]\n|[[Image:Scorpio.svg|20px]]\n|7\n|210\u00b0 to 240\u00b0\n|The [[Scorpion]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]]\n|[[Image:Sagittarius.svg|20px]]\n|8\n|240\u00b0 to 270\u00b0\n|The [[Archery|Archer]] ([[Centaur]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]]\n|[[Image:Capricorn.svg|26px]]\n|9\n|270\u00b0 to 300\u00b0\n|The [[Goat]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]]\n|[[Image:Aquarius.svg|24px]]\n|10\n|300\u00b0 to 330\u00b0\n|The [[water carrier|Water-bearer]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]\n|[[Image:Pisces.svg|20px]]\n|11\n|330\u00b0 to 360\u00b0\n|The [[Fishes]]\n|}\n\n=== Polarity and the four elements ===\n{{main|Triplicity}}\n{{Further|Classical element}}\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n\n[[Image:Sign position example.svg|220px|thumb|right|A simple diagram displaying the planets' sign positions on May 16th, 2012. The signs are colored according to the associated element. Each planet is represented by a [[Astrological symbols|glyph]] next to its longitude within the sign. Additional symbols may be added to represent [[apparent retrograde motion]] ([[File:Retrograde-symbol.svg|11px]]), or apparent stationary moment (shift from retrograde to direct, or vice versa: S).]]\n\n[[Empedocles]], a fifth-century BC Greek philosopher, identified Fire, Earth, Air, and Water as [[classical element|elements]]. He explained the nature of the universe as an interaction of two opposing principles called love and strife manipulating the four elements, and stated that these four elements were all equal, of the same age, that each rules its own province, and each possesses its own individual character. Different mixtures of these elements produced the different natures of things. Empedocles said that those who were born with near equal proportions of the four elements are more intelligent and have the most exact perceptions.<ref name=\"Charlie Higgins\">{{cite web|url=http://accessnewage.com/Articles/astro/HIGELEMS.HTM |title=Astrology and The Four Elements |author=Charlie Higgins |year=1997 |accessdate=2009-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103102752/http://accessnewage.com/articles/astro/HIGELEMS.HTM |archivedate=2010-01-03 |df= }}</ref>\n\nEach sign is associated with one of the [[classical element]]s (fire, air, earth, and water),<ref name=\"RobLeo\">Pelletier, Robert, and Leonard Cataldo (1984). ''Be Your Own Astrologer''. London: Pan Books. pp. 43\u201344</ref><ref name=Pottenger>Pottenger, Maritha (1991). ''Astro Essentials''. San Diego: ACS Publications. pp. 31\u201336.</ref> and these can also be grouped according to polarity (positive or negative): Fire and Air signs are considered [[Positive sign (astrology)|positive signs]] while Water and Earth signs are considered [[Negative sign (astrology)|negative signs]]. The four astrological elements are also considered as a direct equivalent to [[Four temperaments|Hippocrates' personality types]] (sanguine = air; choleric = fire; melancholic = earth; phlegmatic = water). A modern approach looks at elements as \"the energy substance of experience\"<ref name=\"Arroyo27\">Arroyo (1989), p. 27.</ref> and the next table tries to summarize their description through keywords.<ref>Arroyo (1989), pp. 30\u201334</ref><ref>Hone (1978), p. 42</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Polarity\n!Element\n!Symbol<ref>Glyphs from the [[alchemical symbol]]ogy.</ref>\n!Keywords\n!Signs\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Positive (Male)<br>(self-expressive)\n| [[Fire (classical element)|Fire]]\n| [[File:Alchemy fire symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Enthusiasm, drive to express self, faith\n|Aries, Leo, Sagittarius\n|-\n| [[Air (classical element)|Air]]\n| [[File:Alchemy air symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Communication, socialization, conceptualization\n|Gemini, Libra, Aquarius\n|- align=center \n|rowspan=\"2\"| Negative (Female)<br>(self-containing)\n| [[Earth (classical element)|Earth]]\n| [[File:Alchemy earth symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Practicality, caution, material world\n|Taurus, Virgo, Capricorn\n|-\n| [[Water (classical element)|Water]]\n| [[File:Alchemy water symbol.svg|20px]]\n| Emotion, empathy, sensitivity\n|Cancer, Scorpio, Pisces\n|- align=center\n|}\nClassification according to element has gained such importance, that some astrologers start their interpretation of a [[natal chart]], by studying the balance of elements shown by the position of [[Planets in astrology|planets]] and [[Angle (astrology)|angles]]<ref>Arroyo (1975). pp.&nbsp;131\u2013140.</ref> (especially the Sun, the Moon and the Ascendant signs).\n\n=== The three modalities ===\n<!-- \n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nEach of the four elements manifests in three modalities: Cardinal, Fixed and Mutable.<ref>Arroyo (1989), p. 29.</ref> As each modality comprehends four signs, these are also known as Quadruplicities.<ref name=\"RobLeo\"/><ref name=Pottenger/> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Modality !! Symbol<ref>As used in Sepharial's \"The Manual of Astrology\"-Brazilian edition (1988) by Editora Nova Fronteira S/A, Rio de Janeiro</ref>!! Keywords<ref>Hone (1978), p. 40</ref><ref>Arroyo (1989), p. 30</ref>!! Signs\n|-\n| [[Cardinal sign (astrology)|Cardinal]] || [[File:Cardinal symbol.svg|20px]] || Action, dynamic, initiative, great force || Aries, Cancer, Libra, Capricorn\n|-\n| [[Fixed sign|Fixed]] || [[File:Fixed symbol.svg|20px]] || Resistance to change, great willpower, inflexible || Taurus, Leo, Scorpio, Aquarius\n|-\n| [[Mutable sign|Mutable]] || [[File:Mutable symbol.svg|20px]] || Adaptability, flexibility, resourcefulness || Gemini, Virgo, Sagittarius, Pisces\n|- align=center\n|}\n\nThe combination of element and modality provides a basic sign characterization. For instance, Capricorn is a cardinal earth sign, meaning that it is associated with action (cardinal modality) in the material world (earth element).<ref>Hone (1978), p. 75</ref> The next table displays the twelve combinations of elements and modalities.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Element\n! scope=\"col\" | Fire\n! scope=\"col\" | Earth\n! scope=\"col\" | Air\n! scope=\"col\" | Water\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Cardinal\n|Aries\n|Capricorn\n|Libra\n|Cancer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fixed\n|Leo\n|Taurus\n|Aquarius\n|Scorpio\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Mutable\n|Sagittarius\n|Virgo\n|Gemini\n|Pisces\n|}\n\n=== Planetary rulerships ===\n{{See also|Domicile (astrology)}}\n[[File:Acta Eruditorum - II astrologia, 1716 \u2013 BEIC 13388141.jpg|thumb|Representation of the western astrological signs in a 1716 ''[[Acta Eruditorum]]'' table illustration]]\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n\nRulership is the connection between [[Planets in astrology|planet]] and correlated sign and [[House (astrology)|house]].<ref>Hone (1978), p. 22</ref> In traditional [[history of astrology|Western astrology]], each sign is ruled by one of the seven visible planets (note that in [[astrology]], the Sun and Moon are termed \"The Lights\" or fixed stars, while the other bodies are called planets or ''wanderers'', i.e. wandering stars as opposed to the fixed stars). The traditional rulerships are as follows: [[Aries (astrology)|Aries]] ([[Mars]]), [[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]] ([[Venus]]), [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]] ([[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]), [[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]] ([[Moon]]), [[Leo (astrology)|Leo]] ([[Sun]]), [[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]] ([[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]), [[Libra (astrology)|Libra]] ([[Venus]]), [[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]] ([[Pluto]]), [[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]] ([[Jupiter]]), [[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]] ([[Saturn]]), [[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]] ([[Uranus]]), and [[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]] ([[Neptune]]).<ref name=\"astrologynow.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astrologynow.com/carolwillis/Rulerships.txt |title=Rulerships |author=Carol Wills |year=2007 |website=astrologynow.com |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070127194954/http://www.astrologynow.com/carolwillis/Rulerships.txt |archivedate=2007-01-27 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shamos |first1=Geoffery |title=Astrology as a Social Framework: The 'Children of Planets', 1400\u20131600 |journal=[[Journal for the Study of Religion, Nature and Culture]] |date=2013 |volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=434\u2013460 |doi=10.1558/jsrnc.v7i4.434}}</ref>\n\n[[Psychological astrology|Psychologically-oriented]] astrologers often believe that [[Saturn]] is the ruler or co-ruler of Aquarius instead of Uranus; [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]] is the ruler or co-ruler of Pisces instead of Jupiter, and that [[Pluto (mythology)|Pluto]] is the ruler or co-ruler of Scorpio instead of Mars. Some astrologers<ref name=\"Planet Waves\">{{cite web|title=Chiron as True Ruler of Virgo?|accessdate= July 18, 2014|url= http://www.planetwaves.net/cainer/archive/003530.php}}</ref> believe that the planetoid [[Chiron]] may be the ruler of Virgo, while other group of modern astrologers claim that [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] is the ruler of Taurus instead.\n\n===Dates table===\nThe following table shows both traditional<ref name=\"astrologynow.com\"/> and modern<ref>Hone (1978), p. 21.</ref> rulerships.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Symbol\n!Unicode <br>{{abbr|Char|Character}}\n!Sign names\n!Dates \n!Ruling <br>celestial body<br>\nModern\n!Ruling <br>celestial body<br>\nClassical\n|-\n|[[Image:Aries.svg|20px]]\n|\u2648\n|[[Aries (astrology)|Aries]]\n|March 21 \u2013 April 19\n|Mars\n|Mars\n|-\n|[[Image:Taurus.svg|20px]]\n|\u2649\n|[[Taurus (astrology)|Taurus]]\n|April 20 \u2013 May 20\n|Venus\n|Venus\n|-\n|[[Image:Gemini.svg|20px]]\n|\u264a\n|[[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]]\n|May 21 \u2013 June 20\n|Mercury\n|Mercury\n|-\n|[[Image:Cancer.svg|20px]]\n|\u264b\n|[[Cancer (astrology)|Cancer]]\n|June 21 \u2013 July 22\n|Moon\n|Moon\n|-\n|[[Image:Leo.svg|20px]]\n|\u264c\n|[[Leo (astrology)|Leo]]\n|July 23 \u2013 August 22\n|Sun\n|Sun\n|-\n|[[Image:Virgo.svg|20px]]\n|\u264d\n|[[Virgo (astrology)|Virgo]]\n|August 23 \u2013 September 22\n|Mercury\n|Earth\n|-\n|[[Image:Libra.svg|25px]]\n|\u264e\n|[[Libra (astrology)|Libra]]\n|September 23 \u2013 October 22\n|Venus\n|Venus\n|-\n|[[Image:Scorpio.svg|20px]]\n|\u264f\n|[[Scorpio (astrology)|Scorpio]]\n|October 23 \u2013 November 21\n|Pluto\n|Mars\n|-\n|[[Image:Sagittarius.svg|20px]]\n|\u2650\n|[[Sagittarius (astrology)|Sagittarius]]\n|November 22 \u2013 December 21\n|Jupiter\n|Jupiter\n|-\n|[[Image:Capricorn.svg|25px]]\n|\u2651\n|[[Capricorn (astrology)|Capricorn]]\n|December 22 \u2013 January 19\n|Saturn\n|Saturn\n|-\n|[[Image:Aquarius.svg|25px]]\n|\u2652\n|[[Aquarius (astrology)|Aquarius]]\n|January 20 \u2013 February 18\n|Uranus\n|Saturn\n|-\n|[[Image:Pisces.svg|20px]]\n|\u2653\n|[[Pisces (astrology)|Pisces]]\n|February 19 \u2013 March 20\n|Neptune\n|Jupiter\n|-\n|}\n\nThe twelves signs each have opposites, resulting in six opposite couples. Fire and Air elements are opposites and Earth and Water elements are opposites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/opposizione|title=Opposition|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref> Spring signs are opposite to autumn ones, and winter signs are opposite to summer ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2994-aria|title=The element of Air|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2992-fuoco|title=The element of Fire|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2993-acqua|title=The element of Water|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dichesegnosei.it/elementi/2995-terra|title=The element of Earth|website=dichesegnosei.it|language=it}}</ref>\n* Aries is opposite to Libra\n* Cancer is opposite to Capricorn\n* Gemini is opposite to Sagittarius\n* Pisces is opposite to Virgo\n* Taurus is opposite to Scorpio\n* Leo is opposite to Aquarius\n\n=== Dignity and detriment, exaltation and fall ===\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nA traditional belief of astrology, known as [[essential dignity]], is the idea that the Sun, Moon and planets are more powerful and effective in some signs than others, because the basic nature of both is held to be in harmony. By contrast, they are held to find some signs to be weak or difficult to operate in because their natures are thought to be in conflict. The most important of these categories are Dignity, Detriment, Exaltation and Fall.\n\n* '''[[Essential dignity|Dignity]]''' and '''[[Detriment (astrology)|Detriment]]''': A [[Planets in astrology|planet]] is strengthened or '''dignified''' if it falls within the sign that it rules. In other words, it is said to exercise ''[[Domicile (astrology)|Rulership]]'' of the sign. For example, the Moon in Cancer is considered \"strong\" (well-dignified). Seventeenth century astrologer [[William Lilly]] compared rulership to a king on his throne, with considerable dignity. If a planet is in the sign opposite that which it rules (or is dignified), it is said to be weakened or in '''Detriment''' (for example, the Moon in Capricorn).<ref name=\"glossary\">\"Glossary of Astrological Terms\". Logos, Asaa 1998\u20132004. 26 Nov 2007. {{cite web|url=http://logosastrology.dk/glossary.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080122142135/http://logosastrology.dk/glossary.htm |archivedate=2008-01-22 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn traditional astrology, other levels of Dignity are recognised in addition to Rulership. These are known as Exaltation (see below), [[Triplicity]], [[Terms or bounds]], and Face or [[Decans|Decan]], which together are known as describing a planet's ''[[Essential dignity]]'', the quality or ability to give of one's true nature. Contemporary traditional astrologers like [[John Frawley (astrologer)|John Frawley]] or [[J Lee Lehman]] explain further on the concept of Essential Dignity.<ref name=\"glossary\" />\n\n* '''[[Exaltation (astrology)|Exaltation]]''' and '''[[Astrological fall|Fall]]''': In addition, a planet is also strengthened when it is in its sign of '''Exaltation'''. In traditional horary astrology, Exaltation denotes a level of dignity somewhat exaggerated compared to rulership. Exaltation was considered to give the planet (or what it signified in a horary chart) dignity, with the metaphor of an honoured guest \u2013 who is the centre of attention but the extent of their ability to act is limited. Examples of planets in their Exaltation are: Saturn (Libra), Sun (Aries), Venus (Pisces), Moon (Taurus), Mercury (Virgo, although some disagree to this classification), Mars (Capricorn), Jupiter (Cancer). A planet in the opposite sign of its Exaltation is said to be in its '''Fall''', and thus weakened, perhaps seemingly more so than Detriment. The Planet in fall is passively rejected or ignored by the sign that it's in. It can be likened to a mayor of a rival city trying to make suggestions to the hosting mayor for how he should run his city: The host mayor finds it difficult to trust him and cannot see how his input could have relevancy to his city. The people of the city feel the same as their ruler. The result is impasse and failure on behalf of both mayors and the city.<ref name=\"glossary\" /> There is no agreement as to the signs in which the three extra-Saturnian planets may be considered to be exalted.<ref>Hone (1978), p. 144</ref>\n\nThe following table summarizes the positions described above:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Planet (Symbol) !! Dignity !! Detriment !! Exaltation !! Fall\n|-\n| '''Sun''' ([[File:Sun symbol.svg|15px|Sol]]) || Leo || Cancer || Aries || Libra\n|-\n| '''Moon''' ([[File:Moon symbol crescent.svg|15px|First quarter moon]]) || Cancer || Leo || Taurus || Scorpio\n|-\n| '''Mercury''' ([[File:Mercury symbol.svg|15px|Mercury]]) || Gemini || Sagittarius and Pisces || Aquarius || Leo\n|-\n| '''Venus''' ([[File:Venus symbol.svg|15px|Venus]]) || Libra and Taurus || Aries and Scorpio || Pisces || Virgo\n|-\n| '''Mars''' ([[File:Mars symbol.svg|15px|Mars]]) || Aries and Scorpio || Libra and Taurus || Capricorn || Cancer\n|-\n| '''Jupiter''' ([[File:Jupiter symbol.svg|15px|Jupiter]]) || Sagittarius and Pisces || Gemini and Virgo || Cancer || Capricorn\n|-\n| '''Saturn''' ([[File:Saturn symbol.svg|15px|Saturn]]) || Capricorn and Aquarius || Cancer and Leo || Libra || Aries\n|-\n!Earth \n|Virgo\n|Scorpio\n|Leo\n|Cancer\n|}\n\nIn addition to essential dignity, the traditional astrologer considers ''[[Accidental dignity]]'' of planets. This is placement by [[astrological house|house]] in the chart under examination. Accidental dignity is the planet's \"ability to act.\" So we might have, for example, Moon in Cancer, dignified by rulership, is placed in the 12th house it would have little scope to express its good nature.<ref>{{cite web|title=Accidental Dignity|publisher= Astrological Dictionary 1998\u20132007|website= www.gotohoroscope.com|date= 26 November 2007|url= http://www.gotohoroscope.com/dictionary/astrological/5.html}}</ref> The 12th is a cadent house as are the 3rd, 6th and 9th and planets in these houses are considered weak or afflicted. On the other hand, Moon in the 1st, 4th, 7th or 10th would be more able to act as these are Angular houses. Planets in Succedent houses of the chart (2nd, 5th, 8th, 11th) are generally considered to be of medium ability to act. Besides Accidental Dignity, there are a range of ''Accidental Debilities'', such as retrogradation, Under the Sun's Beams, Combust, and so forth.\n\n=== Additional classifications ===\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n{{Details|Decans}}\nEach sign can be divided into three 10\u00b0 sectors known as decans or decanates, though these have fallen into disuse. The first decanate is said to be most emphatically of its own nature and is ruled by the sign ruler.<ref>Hone (1978), p.&nbsp;87</ref> The next decanate is sub-ruled by the planet ruling the next sign in the same triplicity. The last decanate is sub-ruled by the next in order in the same triplicity.<ref>Hone (1978), p.&nbsp;88</ref>\n\nWhile the element and modality of a sign are together sufficient to define it, they can be grouped to indicate their symbolism. The first four signs, Aries, Taurus, Gemini and Cancer, form the group of personal signs. The next four signs, Leo, Virgo, Libra and Scorpio form the group of interpersonal signs. The last four signs of the zodiac, Sagittarius, Capricorn, Aquarius and Pisces, form the group of transpersonal signs.<ref name=\"spiritsingles.com\">\"An Introduction to Astrology.\" Spiritsingles.com 25 Nov.2007. {{cite web|url=http://www.spiritsingles.com/Astrology/aboutAstrology.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209083130/http://www.spiritsingles.com/Astrology/aboutAstrology.cfm |archivedate=2007-12-09 |df= }}</ref>\n\nDane Rudhyar presented the tropical zodiac primary factors,<ref>Rudhyar (1943)</ref> used in the curriculum of the RASA School of Astrology. The tropical zodiac is the zodiac of seasonal factors as opposed to the sidereal zodiac (constellation factors). The primary seasonal factors are based on the changing ratio of sunlight and darkness across the year. The first factor is whether the chosen time falls in the half of the year when daylight is increasing, or the half of the year when darkness is increasing. The second factor is whether the chosen time falls in the half of the year when there is more daylight than darkness, or the half when there is more darkness than daylight. The third factor is which of the four seasons the chosen time falls in, defined by the first two factors. Thus<ref name=ArmstrongFactors>{{cite web|title=The Signs and the Houses|first= Robin |last=Armstrong|publisher= RASA School of Astrology|year= 2009 |url=http://www.rasa.ws/index.php/rasa-library-articles-signs-and-houses-}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=I Ching: The Sequence of Change|first= Robin|last= Armstrong|publisher= RA Publications |year=2009 |url=http://thewakingdream.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1392&Itemid=1551}}</ref> \n* The ''winter'' season is when daylight is increasing and there is more darkness than daylight.\n* The ''spring'' season is when daylight is increasing and there is more daylight than darkness.\n* The ''summer'' season is when darkness is increasing and there is more daylight than darkness.\n* The ''autumn'' season is when darkness is increasing and there is more darkness than daylight.\n\n== Indian astrology ==\n{{further|Hindu astrology}}\nIn Indian astrology, there are five elements: fire, earth, air, water, and ether. The master of fire is Mars, while Mercury is of earth, Saturn of air, Venus of water, and Jupiter of ether.\n\n[[Jyotish]] astrology recognises twelve zodiac signs (R\u0101\u015bi),<ref>Sutton (1999) pp. 74\u201392.</ref> that correspond to those in Western astrology. The relation of the signs to the elements is the same in the two systems.\n\n=== Nakshatras ===\n{{main|Nakshatra}}\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nA '''nakshatra''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0928\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u094d\u0930, [[Sanskrit]] ''{{IAST|nakshatra}}'', from ''{{IAST|naksha-}}'' 'map', and ''{{IAST|tra-}}'' 'guard') or '''lunar mansion''' is one of the 27 divisions of the sky, identified by the prominent star(s) in them, as used in [[Hindu astronomy]] and [[Jyotisha|astrology]] ([[Jyotisha]]).<ref>Sutton (1999), p.&nbsp;168.</ref>Nakshatra in Sanskrit and Tamil means a star.\n\n<br />\n\n== Chinese zodiac signs ==\n{{main|Chinese zodiac}}\n\nChinese astrological signs operate on cycles of years, lunar months, and two-hour periods of the day (also known as ''shichen''). A particular feature of the Chinese zodiac is its operation in a [[Sexagenary cycle|60-year cycle]] in combination with the [[Wu Xing|Five Phases]] of [[Chinese astrology]] ([[Wood (Wu Xing)|Wood]], [[Fire (Wu Xing)|Fire]], [[Metal (Wu Xing)|Metal]], [[Water (Wu Xing)|Water]] and [[Earth (Wu Xing)|Earth]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://big5.china.com.cn/culture/txt/2009-02/16/content_17286701.htm |title='Almanac' 'lunar' zodiac beginning of spring as the boundary dislocation? \u2013 China Network |date=16 February 2009 |accessdate=5 January 2011}}</ref>\nNevertheless, some researches say that there is an obvious relationship between the Chinese 12-year cycle and zodiac constellations: each year of the cycle corresponds to a certain disposal of Jupiter. For example, in the year of [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] Jupiter is in the Sign of Gemini, in the year of [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] Jupiter is in the Sign of Cancer and so on. So the Chinese 12-year calendar is a solar-lunar-jovian calendar.\n\n=== Zodiac symbolism ===\nThe following table shows the twelve signs and their attributes.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Sign\n!Yin/Yang\n!Direction\n!Season\n!Fixed Element\n!Trine\n|-\n|[[Mouse (zodiac)|Mouse]]\n|Yang\n|North\n|Mid-Winter\n|Water\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]]\n|Yin\n|North\n|Late Winter\n|Earth\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]]\n|Yang\n|East\n|Early Spring\n|Wood\n|3rd\n|-\n|[[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]]\n|Yin\n|East\n|Mid-Spring\n|Wood\n|4th\n|-\n|[[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]]\n|Yang\n|East\n|Late Spring\n|Earth\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]]\n|Yin\n|South\n|Early Summer\n|Fire\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]]\n|Yang\n|South\n|Mid-Summer\n|Fire\n|3rd\n|-\n|[[Sheep (zodiac)|Sheep]]\n|Yin\n|South\n|Late Summer\n|Earth\n|4th\n|-\n|[[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]]\n|Yang\n|West\n|Early Autumn\n|Metal\n|1st\n|-\n|[[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]]\n|Yin\n|West\n|Mid-Autumn\n|Metal\n|2nd\n|-\n|[[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]]\n|Yang\n|West\n|Late Autumn\n|Earth\n|3rd\n|-\n|[[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]]\n|Yin\n|North\n|Early Winter\n|Water\n|4th\n|}\n\n=== The twelve signs ===\n\n[[Image:China 24 cardinal directions.png|thumb|250px|Chart showing the 24 cardinal directions and the symbols of the sign associated with them.]]\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\nIn [[Chinese astrology]], the zodiac of twelve animal sign represents twelve different types of personality. The zodiac traditionally begins with the sign of the [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]], and there are many stories about the [[Origins of the Chinese Zodiac]] which explain why this is so. When the twelve zodiac signs are part of the 60-year calendar in combination with the four elements, they are traditionally called the twelve [[Earthly Branches]]. The Chinese zodiac follows the [[Lunisolar calendar|lunisolar]] [[Chinese calendar]]<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Novak|first1=Sarah|title=The Chinese Zodiac|journal=Faces|volume=34|pages=42}}</ref> and thus the \"changeover\" days in a month (when one sign changes to another sign) vary each year. The following are the twelve zodiac signs in order.<ref name=Lau>Theodora Lau, ''Ibid'', pp. 2\u20138, 30\u20135, 60\u20134, 88\u201394, 118\u201324, 148\u201353, 178\u201384, 208\u201313, 238\u201344, 270\u201378, 306\u201312, 338\u201344, 2005</ref>\n\n# {{lang|zh|\u5b50}} [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] (Yang, 1st Trine, Fixed Element Water): [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] years include 1900, 1912, 1924, 1936, 1948, 1960, 1972, 1984, 1996, 2008, 2020, 2032. The [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] are 11pm \u2013 1am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u4e11}} [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] (Yin, 2nd Trine, Fixed Element Earth:<ref name=\"Wu\" /> [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] years include 1901, 1913, 1925, 1937, 1949, 1961, 1973, 1985, 1997, 2009, 2021, 2033. The [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]] are 1am \u2013 3am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u5bc5}} [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] (Yang, 3rd Trine, Fixed Element Wood): [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] years include 1902, 1914, 1926, 1938, 1950, 1962, 1974, 1986, 1998, 2010, 2022, 2034. The [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] are 3am \u2013 5am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u536f}} [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] (Yin, 4th Trine, Fixed Element Wood): [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] Years include 1903, 1915, 1927, 1939, 1951, 1963, 1975, 1987, 1999, 2011, 2023, 2035. The [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]] are 5am \u2013 7am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u8fb0}} [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] (Yang, 1st Trine, Fixed Element Earth<ref name=\"Wu\" />): [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] years include 1904, 1916, 1928, 1940, 1952, 1964, 1976, 1988, 2000, 2012, 2024, 2036. The [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]] are 7am \u2013 9am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u5df3}} [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] (Yin, 2nd Trine, Fixed Element Fire): [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] years include 1905, 1917, 1929, 1941, 1953, 1965, 1977, 1989, 2001, 2013, 2025, 2037. The [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] are 9am \u2013 11am.\n# {{lang|zh|\u5348}} [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] (Yang, 3rd Trine, Fixed Element Fire): [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] years include 1906, 1918, 1930, 1942, 1954, 1966, 1978, 1990, 2002, 2014, 2026, 2038. The [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]] are 11am \u2013 1pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u672a}} [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] (Yin, 4th Trine, Fixed Element Earth<ref name=\"Wu\" />): [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] years include 1907, 1919, 1931, 1943, 1955, 1967, 1979, 1991, 2003, 2015, 2027, 2039. The [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] are 1pm \u2013 3pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u7533}} [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] (Yang, 1st Trine, Fixed Element Metal): [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] years include 1908, 1920, 1932, 1944, 1956, 1968, 1980, 1992, 2004, 2016, 2028, 2040. The [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] are 3pm \u2013 5pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u9149}} [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] (Yin, 2nd Trine, Fixed Element Metal): [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] years include 1909, 1921, 1933, 1945, 1957, 1969, 1981, 1993, 2005, 2017, 2029, 2041. The [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]] are 5pm \u2013 7pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u620c}} [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] (Yang, 3rd Trine, Fixed Element Earth<ref name=\"Wu\" />): [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] years include 1910, 1922, 1934, 1946, 1958, 1970, 1982, 1994, 2006, 2018, 2030, 2042. The [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]] are 7pm \u2013 9pm.\n# {{lang|zh|\u4ea5}} [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] (Yin, 4th Trine, Fixed Element Water): [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] years include 1911, 1923, 1935, 1947, 1959, 1971, 1983, 1995, 2007, 2019, 2031, 2043. The [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] also corresponds to a particular month in the year. The hours of the [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]] are 9pm \u2013 11pm.\n\n=== The five elements ===\n\n<!-- \n     HIDDEN EDITOR NOTE:\n     DO NOT ADD ANY INFORMATION WITHOUT CITING A RELIABLE SOURCE\n     UNSOURCED ADDITIONS WILL BE REMOVED\n-->\n\n* '''[[Tree (Wu Xing)|Wood]]''': The wood person has high morals, is self-confident, expansive and co-operative, with wide and varied interests and idealistic goals. The direction associated with Wood is East, and the season is spring, which makes it the fixed element for the animal signs [[Tiger (zodiac)|Tiger]] and [[Rabbit (zodiac)|Rabbit]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Fire (Wu Xing)|Fire]]''': The fire person has leadership qualities, dynamic passion, and is decisive, self-confident, positive and assertive. The direction associated with Fire is South, and the season is summer, which makes it the fixed element for the animal signs [[Snake (zodiac)|Snake]] and [[Horse (zodiac)|Horse]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Earth (Wu Xing)|Earth]]''': The earth person is serious, logical and methodical, intelligent, objective and good at planning. The direction associated with Earth is Center.  The season for Earth is the changeover point of the four seasons.  It is the fixed element for the animal signs [[Ox (zodiac)|Ox]], [[Dragon (zodiac)|Dragon]], [[Goat (zodiac)|Goat]] and [[Dog (zodiac)|Dog]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Metal (Wu Xing)|Metal]]''': The metal person is sincere, has fixed values and opinions, is strong of will, and has eloquence of speech.  The direction associated with Metal is West.  The season for Metal is Autumn.  It is the fixed element for the animal signs [[Monkey (zodiac)|Monkey]] and [[Rooster (zodiac)|Rooster]].<ref name=Wu/>\n* '''[[Water (Wu Xing)|Water]]''': The water person is persuasive, intuitive, and empathetic.  The water person is objective and often sought out for their counsel.  The direction associated with water is North.  The season for Water is Winter.  It is the fixed element for the animal signs [[Rat (zodiac)|Rat]] and [[Pig (zodiac)|Pig]].<ref name=Wu/>\n\nThe five elements operate together with the twelve animal signs in a [[Sexagenary cycle|60-year]] calendar. The five elements appear in the calendar in both their yin and yang forms and are known as the ten [[Celestial stem]]s. When trying to calculate the relevant year of the cycle in relation to the [[Gregorian calendar]], an easy rule to follow is that years that end in an even number are Yang (representing masculine, active and light), those that end with an odd number are Yin (representing feminine, passive and darkness).<ref name=Wu>Chinese Astrology:  Exploring the Eastern Zodiac by Shelly Wu</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n== References ==\n*Arroyo, Stephen (1975). ''Astrology, Psychology and The Four Elements''. California: CCRS Publications\n*Arroyo, Stephen (1989). ''Chart Interpretation Handbook''. California: CCRS Publications. {{ISBN|0-916360-49-0}}\n*Bobrick, Benson (2005). ''The Fated Sky: Astrology in History''. Simon & Schuster. 369 pp.\n*Caiozzo, Anna (2003). ''Images of the Sky.'' Paris-Sorbonne. [https://sites.google.com/site/allzodiacs/ Signs and Constellations.]\n*Eric Francis (2016). \"[http://members.planetwaves.net/why-your-zodiac-sign-is-not-wrong/ Why Your Zodiac Sign is Not Wrong]\"\n*Hone, Margaret (1978). ''The Modern Text-Book of Astrology''. Revised edition. England: L. N. Fowler & Co. Ltd. {{ISBN|085243-357-3}}\n*Johnsen, Linda (2004 March). ''A Thousand Suns: Designing Your Future with Vedic Astrology''. Yes International Publishers.\n*Mayo, Jeff (1979). ''Teach Yourself Astrology''. London: Hodder and Stoughton.\n*Rochberg, Francesca (1998), \"Babylonian Horoscopes\", ''American Philosophical Society'', New Series, Vol. 88, No. 1, pp.&nbsp;i\u2013164. {{doi|10.2307/1006632}}. {{JSTOR|1006632}}.\n*[http://www.khaldea.com/rudhyar/pofl/pofl_p1p1.shtml Rudhyar, Dane (1943). ''Astrological Signs \u